{Welcome to the third part of my Anti-Sicilian database which will mostly
cover what to play against the ever-sharp 2...e6 Sicilian and other important
sidelines. In the majority of the chapters, I will be advocating the
fianchetto of the white bishop to g2, combined with a thrust in the centre
d2-d4. I can't always promise an advantage in the end but still, I found the
variations to be fresh and in most cases - very entertaining. I hope you will
enjoy reading this database as much as I did writing it! I would like to
mention that one of the most important lines of the database 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6
3.g3 doesn't bear an official name. I did hear from several sources that it
could be called "King's Indian Attack", however, I think it's not a precise
name as this particular setup refers to the d2-d3 and f2-f4 pawn structure,
followed by an expansion on the kingside, while in most of the lines I will be
advocating for d2-d4. Given the fact that this line is particularly popular
among the top players in the Baltic countries and that it was frequently
played with both colours by my friend, GM Aloyzas Kveinys (who sadly passed
away last year - he was very anxious what I'm going to suggest in this
database back then!), I decided to call it as "The Baltic Variation". I hope
this database will contribute to its popularity and we will see if the name
will stay. As a final note - the purpose of this database is not to offer
everything anti-Sicilian. The main reason why I started to write these
databases is that in the main lines of the Najdorf, Sveshnikov or Taimanov/Kan
Black is doing really well, with a great history of theoretical studies. My
goal was to offer a fresh perspective on how to meet the Sicilian with easy,
less explored gameplans which promise White a good game, thus I came up with
the name "Anti Sicilian". However, if I do see a dubious version of the
Sicilian like 2...a6 or 2...b6, it's very difficult for me to suggest for
White to go for the Anti-Sicilian with the fianchetto of the bishop on g2 if
the open version in that particular moment is so much better. I did try to
keep the database in the same spirit throughout the chapters, mostly choosing
the same setup, but a smart player probably will mix the Anti-Sicilian and
open Sicilian choices for greater success. Please judge yourself!} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 b6 $6 {This continuation has some modest popularity among people who avoid
the main lines of the Sicilian but objectively it's dubious and too slow.
Black is not challenging the centre or developing a piece thus he immediately
lags behind in development.} (2... Qa5 $6 {a very rare move with an intention
to slow down the standard d2-d4. Since there's no immediate way how White can
"punish" Black for this strange move, I suggest to stick to the same strategy
as analyzed in the later chapters - fianchetto the bishop on g2 and go for a
later d2-d4. The black queen on a5 doesn't really contribute anything
significant to Black's position.} 3. g3 ({some sort of Alapin seems to be
working here as well.} 3. c3 Nc6 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. Qe2 d6 6. O-O Bg4 7. Bb3 {
[%cal Gh2h3,Gf1d1,Gd2d4] and so on and so forth - it's not clear what the
black queen is doing on a5.}) 3... g6 {I think White should stick to the rule
- if Black allows, play a quick short castle, followed by c2-c3 and d2-d4. If
Black starts to press on the e4 pawn early with Nf6, then comes the
alternative plan of Nc3 and a later d2-d4.} (3... Nc6 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6.
O-O Bg4 {Black can stop both of these plans at a cost - the light-squared
bishop. Now White can opt for a typical King's Indian attack.} 7. h3 Bxf3 8.
Bxf3 e6 9. d3 Be7 10. Bg2 O-O 11. f4 Rad8 12. g4 Rd7 13. g5 Ne8 14. Qg4 c4 15.
Be3 cxd3 16. cxd3 f5 17. gxf6 Rxf6 18. d4 $16 {1/2-1/2 (56) Holvason,J (2166)
-Goreacinic,D (2286) Germany 2014}) 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Nc6 6. c3 d6 (6... Nf6 7.
e5 Nd5 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd4b3]} Nc7 10. f4 $14) 7. d4
cxd4 8. cxd4 Bg4 (8... Nf6 9. d5 Nb8 10. Nc3 $16) 9. Be3 Qh5 10. Qb3 $1 $14) (
2... Qc7 {the same principle as for 2...Qa5 can be applied also for this rare
move - White can either continue with the fianchetto of the light-squared
bishop on g2, or play an improved version of the Alapin. Many of the lines
after the fianchetto will be transpositional or at least very similar to the
ones covered in later chapters thus I won't analyze them in great depth.
Instead, I will provide a few lines which might be critical for this
particular setup.} 3. g3 (3. c3 {is a very good alternative to consider -
White can play a very good Alapin structure and Black doesn't have access to
the d7-d5 push as the queen seems to be misplaced on c7, at least in such an
early stage of the game.} Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 e6 7. Bd2 $14 {
[%csl Rc7][%cal Gb1c3,Gf1d3]}) 3... Nc6 (3... Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg2 {continued
by 0-0 and d2-d4. I should note that the King's Indian attack is available as
well with d2-d3, Ng5 or Nd2, followed by f2-f4 and g3-g4-g5.}) 4. Bg2 g6 (4...
Nf6 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d4]}) 5. O-O Bg7 6. c3 Nf6 $146 7. d4 $1 {Trying to win a
tempo by not playing Qe2 or Re1 - this motif to sacrifice the pawn on e4 is
already known in other Sicilian lines. White gets a huge compensation for the
pawn should Black accept it.} (7. Re1 O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ne4 11.
Nbd2 {probably is playable as well, but Black's position feels very
comfortable.}) 7... cxd4 (7... Nxe4 8. d5 Nd8 {as long as White won't
concentrate on winning back the pawn immediately but use the positional
benefits, the compensation will be obvious.} 9. Bf4 Qb6 10. Nbd2 $1 Nxd2 11.
Nxd2 d6 (11... Qxb2 12. Re1 $1 $16) 12. Re1 Qc7 13. Qe2 b6 14. Nc4 Nb7 15. a4
$44 h6 16. a5 bxa5 17. Rxa5 $1 O-O (17... g5 18. Rxc5 $1 Qd8 19. Nxd6+ $1 Nxd6
20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Rc6 Qd8 22. d6 {is just an illustration of the tactical
possibilities.}) (17... Nxa5 $4 18. Nxd6+ Kf8 19. Nxf7 $18) 18. Ra6 Bd7 19. Na3
{[%cal Ga3b5]}) 8. cxd4 d5 (8... Nxe4 9. d5 Ne5 (9... Nb4 10. Qe1 $1 {[%cal
Ge1b4,Ge1e4]} Nxg3 11. hxg3 Nc2 12. Qe2 Nxa1 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Be3 $16 {[%cal
Gf1a1]}) 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Re1 f5 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 $14 {[%csl Re7][%cal
Gh2h4,Gc1g5,Ga1b1,Gd1e2] with very good compensation for White as Black
dangerously lags behind in development.}) 9. e5 Ne4 10. Be3 O-O 11. Nfd2 Nxd2
12. Qxd2 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) (2... a6 {will be covered in Chapter 2.}) 3. d4 $1
{As I already mentioned in the foreword, this is probably not the time to play
anti-Sicilian out of some principle - the main line looks really excellent!} ({
Of course, you can still go for the Anti-Sicilian, but the majority of the
free advantage will be gone immediately.} 3. g3 {White can still opt for the
standard approach but this will give Black a good game.} Bb7 4. d3 (4. Nc3 Nf6
5. e5 $2 {unfortunately this typical idea here doesn't work.} Ng4 {[%cal Rg4e5]
}) 4... e6 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O Nf6 {as far as I see it, here White has two
reasonable ideas. 1) Go for the King's Indian Attack with either Nf3-g5 or
Nf3-d2 and continue storming forward with f2-f4 and g3-g4.2) Switch to the
Hedgehog but lose a tempo in the process. In a closed position it shouldn't be
really that important.} 7. Nc3 (7. c4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1 {[%cal Gd3d4]} a6
10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qc7 12. Be3 Nbd7 13. f4 Rac8 14. Rc1 Rfe8 15. b3 Bf8 16.
f5 Ne5 17. h3 {1/2-1/2 (17) Efimenko,Z (2651)-Moiseenko,A (2657) Rivne 2016})
7... Be7 8. Ng5 Nc6 9. f4) 3... cxd4 {as it's common for the Sicilian, if
Black won't take the pawn, White will march forward with d4-d5, gaining a
considerable space advantage.} 4. Nxd4 Bb7 5. Nc3 {Black is at a crossroad -
he should be very careful not to get into immediate trouble.} a6 {pretty much
the only move Black has been playing here recently - he takes care of the b5
square from any Nb5 ideas and hopes to be flexible in the centre. In reality
White is ahead in development for two tempos.} (5... e6 $6 6. Ndb5 {[%cal
Gb5d6,Gc1f4]} d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Nd5 $1 Na6 (8... exf4 $4 9. Nbc7+ Kd7 10. Qg4+
Kc6 11. Bb5+ Kc5 12. b4+ Kd4 13. O-O-O+ Kxe4 14. Rhe1# {a little picturesque
checkmate!}) 9. Be3 $16) (5... Nc6 $6 6. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gd4b5,Gc3d5]} (6. Bg5 {
looks great as well}) 6... g6 7. Nxc6 $1 Bxc6 (7... dxc6 $2 8. Nb5 $1 Rc8 9.
Qf3 $1 $18 {[%cal Ga1d1]}) 8. Qd4 f6 9. e5 $16) (5... g6 6. Bf4 Bg7 7. e5 Nc6
8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Qe2 e6 10. h4 h6 11. O-O-O Ne7 12. Ne4 $16) (5... Nf6 6. Bg5 $1
{the pawn on e4 is not relevant, the piece development is.} Nxe4 (6... e6 7. e5
h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Qe2 $16) 7. Nxe4 Bxe4 8. Qg4 $1 $146
{[%cal Ge1c1,Gd4b5] it should be apparent that this can't end well for Black.}
Bb7 9. Nb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5d6]} f6 10. Bf4 e5 11. Bxe5 fxe5 12. Qh5+ g6 (12... Ke7
13. O-O-O) 13. Qxe5+ Qe7 (13... Kf7 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. Bc4+) 14. Nd6+ Kd8 15.
Nxb7+ Kc8 16. Nd6+ $18) 6. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] I'm sure there's more
than one good setup for White, the only limit is the imagination. With the
text move, White prohibits Black from playing e7-e6 and is looking for a quick
0-0-0.} (6. g3 {As an alternative you can consider sticking to the same setup
as in most of the chapters but I consider the main line to be much stronger.}
e6 7. Bg2 d6 (7... Nf6 {is not precise as now Black will be having some
difficulty to deal with the e4-e5 threat.} 8. O-O Qc7 9. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5]} d6
10. Nd5 $1 {this motif will be covered in later chapters}) 8. O-O Nd7 {If
Black understands the dangers of this variation, he will develop his queenside
pieces first and watch out for the e4-e5 and Nc3-d5 threats.} 9. f4 Qc7 10. g4
{[%cal Gg4g5,Gd1e2,Gc1e3,Ga1e1] This should lead to a double-edged game where
White's chances are somewhat higher. If you do consider playing this, I'll
just mention a few ideas: 1) Discard the need to play a2-a4 - Black didn't
play b5 anyway and if he will consider playing b6-b5-b4, he will be too slow.
2) If Black plays h7-h6, you don't have to crash through with an immediate
g4-g5. Think about where he is going to castle? Perhaps after castling, the
g4-g5 threat will be even more unpleasant. 3) While Black is configuring his
setup, you can continue developing your pieces as the g4-g5 threat will always
be in the air.}) 6... Qc7 (6... d6 7. Bc4 {a fantastic version of the Fischer
- Sozin attack 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Bc4. Do you
see the difference?} Nd7 8. Qe2 b5 9. Bd5 Qc8 10. O-O (10. O-O-O {is more
energetic}) 10... Ngf6 11. Rad1 e6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bxe6 Qc5 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15.
exd5 O-O-O 16. Rd3 Kb7 17. Rc3 Qd4 18. a4 Qe5 19. Be3 Nc5 20. axb5 a5 21. b6
Be7 22. Ra1 Ra8 23. Qb5 Ra6 24. Qc6+ Kb8 25. Qc7+ Ka8 26. b7+ Nxb7 27. Qc8+ {
1-0 (27) Panchenko,A-Psakhis,L (2480) Vilnius 1978}) (6... Nf6 7. e5 Ne4 8.
Nxe4 Bxe4 9. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) 7. Nd5 $1 {immediately exploiting the
awkward strategy that Black has chosen.} Qe5 {What else?} (7... Bxd5 8. exd5
Nf6 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Be2 e6 11. O-O Bd6 12. g3 Be5 13. Bf3 Ra7 14. c3 f5 15.
Re1 O-O 16. Qd2 Bg7 17. Rad1 Rc8 18. a3 Qc5 19. Qg5 Qf8 20. Ne2 Qd8 21. Qf4 Qf6
22. Qe3 e5 23. Bg2 Rb7 24. Bh3 Bh6 25. Qd3 f4 26. gxf4 exf4 27. Kh1 b5 28. Nd4
Rb6 29. Nf5 {1-0 (43) Gordievsky,D (2555)-Mamatov,M (2098) Moscow 2016}) 8. Be3
{[%cal Gd4f3] because of the Nf3 and Nc7 threat Black has to take on d5.} Bxd5
(8... e6 $4 9. Nf3 Qxe4 10. Nc7+ Ke7 11. Nxa8 Bxa8 12. Qd4 Qxd4 13. Bxd4 $18 {
1-0 (53) Groszpeter,A (2478)-Berezjuk,S (2343) Pardubice 2000}) 9. exd5 Nf6 (
9... Qxd5 10. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3]} e5 11. Nf5 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Nc6 13. O-O Nf6 14.
Bf3 $16 {White has a fantastic compensation for the sacrificed pawn and much
more than that.} e4 15. Be2 h6 16. a4 d5 17. Bxb6 g6 18. Ne3 d4 19. Bxd4 Nxd4
20. Rxd4 Be7 21. a5 O-O 22. b4 {1-0 (40) Huschenbeth,N (2581)-Dann,M (2488)
Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2017}) 10. Bc4 {Black is clearly struggling with
his development.} e6 (10... Nxd5 11. Qf3 $16 e6 (11... Nxe3 12. fxe3 {[%cal
Gf3f7,Gf3a8]}) 12. Bxd5 Qxd5 13. Qxd5 exd5 14. O-O-O Nc6 15. Rhe1 Kd8 16. Nf5
$16) 11. dxe6 $146 dxe6 12. Qf3 Qe4 13. Be2 Nbd7 14. Qxe4 Nxe4 15. Bf3 Ndf6 16.
g4 h6 17. h4 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gg4g5] Perhaps White is even strategically
winning.} *

