1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6 {This odd move has an interesting background - the
potential follow-up 3.d4, leading to an open Sicilian, supposedly is not good.
Obviously, that's not what I'm going to suggest to you! Sometimes we will
switch to open Sicilian but only when we have really great prospects.} 3. g3 $5
{staying consistent - this fianchetto of the bishop will be the main
continuation in the majority of the chapters of this database. This will also
help you to easier remember the lines which from time to time will be
transpositional to other chapters.} ({One of the most popular approaches is to
treat this position as Alapin.} 3. c3 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 {I spent some time
analyzing the lines and realized that the inclusion of 2...a6 doesn't do any
great damage for Black to play the Alapin (it is not among the main moves so
early) but still Black remains solid and can even force White to play
positions with an isolated pawn on d4. Thus, I discarded this continuation
quite quickly as you will need to have some knowledge of the Alapin structures
to play it properly.} Bg4 6. Be2 e6 7. Be3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf6 9. Nc3 {is a
sample line.}) (3. d4 {in my childhood I was taught that you never, ever play
this move after 2...a6! As a matter of fact, it's not really bad, White can
even recapture on d4 with the queen and then retreat, but still, I find the
main line to be so much more interesting.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {this is
the point of Black's strategy - White has no access to the b5 point and the
incoming Bf8-b4 is an annoying threat.} 6. Nf3 Bb4) 3... b5 {If Black plays
something else, many lines will be highly transpositional to other chapters or
at least very similar, depending on how Black will play out the opening.} (3...
Nc6 $5 {this is an interesting alternative for Black! Now White can't
transpose to the Rossolimo. Black is quite flexible but still, he can't be
really happy about the a7-a6 move as it often doesn't contribute anything
important. Perhaps Black is just happy that White didn't play the Rossolimo?}
4. Bg2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gc2c3,Gd2d4] White's plan in most occasions will remain
the same - short castle, followed by c2-c3 and d2-d4.} g6 {the most played move
} (4... d6 5. c3 {it in White's best interest to grab the centre as quickly as
possible.} Nf6 (5... Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 e5 9. Be3 $1 $14 {
[%cal Gb1c3,Ge1g1] if you've read my first database on the anti-Najdorf
approach, this continuation very much resembles one of the topical chapters.})
6. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gd1a4,Ga4e4] also a known idea from the Anti-Najdorf
database! The pawn on e4 is indirectly defended.} cxd4 7. cxd4 d5 (7... Nxe4 $2
8. d5 Qa5+ 9. Nfd2 $1 {and Black unexpectedly loses material!}) 8. e5 Ne4 9.
O-O {and the position quite inevitably transforms into known ideas.} e6 (9... Bg4
{doesn't really help as} 10. h3 Bh5 {is risky because of the nice intermezzo}
11. e6 $1 fxe6 12. g4 Bf7 13. Nc3 $14 {and you can find a similar position in
the Anti-Najdorf database. White is better.}) 10. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gf3e1,Gf2f3]
and we're back to the French Defence.}) (4... Nf6 5. d3 {I think this is more
accurate than Nc3 as perhaps White will need to return to the idea to play
c2-c3 and d3-d4 later.} (5. e5 $5 $146 Ng4 6. c3 Ngxe5 7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. d4 cxd4
9. cxd4 Ng6 10. Nc3 e6 11. d5 $44 {is the engine's choice! I did not analyze
it in detail but I thought I should mention it.}) 5... d6 (5... e5 {it's odd
that after this move the position essentially transforms to a very important
line, covered in Chapter 8! Here Black has managed to make an extra tempo with
a7-a6, but it doesn't change anything.} 6. O-O Be7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Nd2 {[%cal
Gd2c4,Gf2f4]} d6 9. Nc4 Bg4 10. f3 Be6 11. f4 exf4 {and the difference is that
here White can actually play} 12. Bxf4 $5 {as Black has an extra weakness on
b6 to worry about.}) 6. O-O g6 (6... e6 7. c3 Be7 8. Qe2 O-O 9. d4 d5 10. e5
Ne4 11. Be3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gf3e1,Gf2f3] with the standard idea, analyzed in
detail in Chapter 9.}) 7. Re1 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gd3d4]} e5 (7... Bg7 $6 8. e5 dxe5
9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Rxe5 $14) 8. Bg5 Bg7 9. Nc3 h6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nd2 O-O 12.
Nd5 Bg7 13. Nc4 {with an edge for White.}) (4... e5 {if Black either now or a
few moves later fixes the center with the pawn on e5, you can execute a good
plan that will be analyzed in depth in Chapter 8, and also mentioned in this
chapter later. White's plan is simple - Nc3, d2-d3, 0-0, Nd2-c4 and f2-f4.
It's not clear how a7-a6 is helping Black.} 5. O-O g6 $5 6. d3 Bg7 7. Nc3 {
[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Gf2f4]} Nge7 8. Nd2 $5 $146 O-O 9. Nc4 d6 10. f4 {White's
game looks easy.}) (4... e6 5. O-O {and something similar will be analyzed in
later chapters, and not always Black will find the move a7-a6 useful.}) 5. c3
$1 $146 {I do find it quite unbelievable that this logical move is already a
technical novelty! It's very important that in this line White seizes the
control of the centre very quickly. No matter what Black is doing, White is
enjoying a very good version of the Alapin variation.} ({after} 5. O-O Bg7 6.
c3 e5 {[%cal Rg8e7,Re8g8] things are not so simple anymore.}) 5... Bg7 (5... d5
6. exd5 Qxd5 7. O-O {[%cal Gd2d4]} Qd3 8. Ne1 Qd6 9. Na3 Be6 10. d3 $14) (5...
Nf6 6. e5 Nd5 7. O-O Bg7 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 $1 $14 {if you will read later
chapters, you will find this idea to be employed yet again!}) 6. d4 cxd4 7.
cxd4 d6 (7... Qb6 $6 {[%cal Rb6d4,Rc6d4,Rg7b2] this idea, as you might know
from a similar line in the English variation, quickly targeting the central
pawn with everything you've got, simply doesn't work for the aggressor.} 8. Nc3
$1 {of course, the same refutation works also here.} Nxd4 $2 {is losing} 9. Nd5
Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Qd6 11. Bf4 Be5 12. Rc1 $18 {and White already has the decisive
attack}) (7... d5 8. exd5 Qxd5 9. Nc3 Qh5 10. d5 Ne5 11. h3 $1 $16 {looks very
suspicious for Black.}) 8. Be3 $14 {and White has a solid advantage.}) (3... d6
{if Black continues in the spirit of the Najdorf, also here he will find that
the a7-a6 move doesn't contribute much to the particular position. It doesn't
mean it's not playable.} 4. Bg2 Nf6 (4... Nc6 5. c3 $1 {[%cal Gd2d4] similarly
like with 3...Nc6, and 4...d6, White quickly grabs the centre.} Nf6 6. d4 $1 {
is already covered in a different variation.}) 5. e5 $1 {probably is the best
plan which underlines how useless the a6 move was for Black.} dxe5 6. Nxe5 {
[%cal Gg2a8]} Qc7 7. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gb1c3,Ga2a5,Gd2d3,Ge5c4,Gc1f4]})
4. d4 $1 {This is a very rare move but according to my analysis I think it's
the strongest and the most accurate continuation.} ({The problem with the
natural} 4. Bg2 {is that after} Bb7 {White is forced to take care of the e4
pawn by either playing Nc3, Qe2 or d3 - essentially the moves which I
recommend to avoid to play so early! In the main line you will understand why.}
5. d3 (5. d4 {doesn't switch to the main line as Black can play} Bxe4 6. dxc5
e6 {looks just unclear.})) 4... cxd4 {If Black won't take the pawn, White will
move the d-pawn forward and gain some space advantage.} (4... Bb7 5. d5 {
[%csl Rb7]} Nf6 6. Nfd2 $1 ({not} 6. Qe2 e6 7. c4 bxc4 8. Nc3 exd5 9. exd5+ Qe7
10. Qxe7+ Bxe7 11. Bxc4 d6 $11 {[%cal Rb8d7,Rd7b6]}) 6... e6 7. Bg2 $1 {
as it happens, the pawn on d5 is indirectly protected - Black can't take it.}
d6 (7... exd5 $2 8. e5 $1 Ne4 (8... Qe7 9. O-O Qxe5 10. Re1 Ne4 11. Nxe4 dxe4
12. Bxe4 Bxe4 13. Bf4 Qe6 14. Nc3 f5 15. f3 $18) 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Nc3 d5 11.
exd6 Bxd6 12. Nxe4 O-O 13. O-O $16) 8. O-O {the most accurate} (8. c4 {allows
an extra check} exd5 9. exd5 Qe7+ {although the computer insists that White is
just fine after} 10. Ne4 $5 Nxe4 11. O-O $14 {[%cal Gf1e1]}) 8... exd5 9. exd5
{and it's very risky for Black to accept the poisoned pawn.} Be7 (9... Nxd5 $4
10. Nb3) (9... Bxd5 $6 10. Bxd5 Nxd5 11. Ne4 Nc7 12. Bg5 $16) 10. c4 O-O 11.
Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rb7] White has a solid space advantage.}) 5. Bg2 (5. Nxd4 {
probably is the same.}) 5... Bb7 (5... Qa5+ {trying to keep the pawn for the
time being probably is not a great idea.} 6. Nbd2 (6. c3 $5 dxc3 7. Nxc3 {
also is excellent for White.}) 6... Nc6 {[%cal Re7e5]} 7. e5 $1 {[%cal Ge1g1,
Gd2b3,Gb3d4] and White inevitably wins the pawn back.}) 6. Nxd4 Nf6 {this is
the critical position of the opening - so far everyone here was playing either
Nc3 or Qe2. I found a better continuation!} (6... e6 7. O-O Nc6 8. c3 Nf6 9.
Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5] this position will be covered in Chapter 5.}) 7. O-O $1 $146
{a very powerful but logical novelty! According to my analysis, it's very risky
for Black to take the pawn on e4 as he will be walking a tightrope to avoid
the onslaught once White starts his attack. However, if Black can't take on e4
now, then White freely continues with Re1 and threatens to play e4-e5 with
serious consequences. Notice how White avoided playing Qe2 or Nc3 - after
White will play a2-a4, Black's typical response b5-b4 no longer forces White
to move with his knight from c3 as it's not even there.} e6 {not forced but
White's ideas remain the same.} (7... Bxe4 $6 {Not good - I did not find a
single line afterwards which Black could call satisfying. Now White has plenty
of beautiful attacking ideas.} 8. Bxe4 Nxe4 9. Re1 Nf6 (9... d5 {[%csl Rc6]
from afar it might not be easy to understand that Black is in deep trouble
because of the weakened c6 square!} 10. Nc3 $1 {Black can either try to keep
the pawn or give it back but it doesn't change the fact that his king is
coming under a very strong attack. Just enjoy the beautiful lines!} Nxc3 (10...
Nf6 11. Bg5 b4 (11... e6 $4 12. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3d5]} gxf6 13. Qh5 $18 {[%cal
Gd4e6]}) 12. Bxf6 bxc3 (12... gxf6 13. Ne6 $1 fxe6 14. Qh5+ Kd7 15. Nxd5 exd5
16. Qxd5+ Kc7 17. Qxa8 $16) 13. Be5 Qc8 (13... Nd7 $2 14. Nc6 Qb6 15. Bxg7 $1
