1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 {Behold - the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon! Black intends to
play some version of the Dragon but by delaying Nc6 and d6. If Black would
play 2...Nc6, we can play the Rossolimo with 3.Bb5! If Black would play 2...d6,
I advocate 3.Bb5+ and the Moscow variation. Thus the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon
is something we need to address. Generally, there are two very popular setups -
either White treats this position as some sort of a great version of the
Sicilian Alapin and goes for c2-c3 and d2-d4, or plays the Open Sicilian but
setups the Maroczy Bind. Since I'm a big fan of the latter and mostly relied
on it in the first part of my Anti Najdorf approach, that's what I'm going to
suggest to you.} 3. d4 (3. c3 d5 4. e5 Nc6 5. d4 {is the 2nd possibility and
quite popular even at the highest level.}) ({If you are concerned that after 3.
d4 Black will switch to a classical Dragon, you can start with this move order.
} 3. c4 $5 Bg7 ({or} 3... Nc6 4. d4 Bg7 5. dxc5 Qa5+ 6. Bd2 Qxc5 7. Nc3 $14 {
[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Ga1c1]}) 4. d4 Qa5+ $5 {one of the trickiest possible
sidelines should you prefer 3.c4 over 3.d4} (4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 {transforms to
the main lines}) (4... d6 {if Black is trying to swindle you with a tricky
version of the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon, you can always close the position and
immediately get a space advantage.} 5. d5 (5. dxc5 $6 {is not a good choice}
dxc5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nc3 Bxc3+ $5 8. bxc3 Nc6 $11 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] and for
Black it might be easier to organize a game against White's double pawns than
for White to prove the power of the two bishops.}) ({I was considering to
suggest to play} 5. Be2 {but I found no good strategic continuations after the
best} Qb6 $1 6. dxc5 dxc5 {[%csl Rd4] is not what White should be aiming for.})
5... e6 (5... b5 $5 {would be a strange version of the Benko gambit - if you
don't want it, you don't have to accept it and you can choose to play
positionally.} 6. cxb5 a6 7. b6 $5 {the simplest choice} Nf6 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. Bd3
O-O 10. O-O Nxb6 11. h3 $14) 6. Nc3 exd5 7. exd5 $14 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1] the
position remains symmetrical but Black has a weakness on d6 thus he is
slightly worse.}) (4... Qb6 5. dxc5 Qxc5 6. Be2 d6 7. O-O Nc6 8. h3 Qb6 9. Qc2
Nd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 $16 11. Nd2 Bg7 12. Nb3 Nf6 13. Be3 Qc7 14. Rac1 O-O 15. c5
dxc5 16. Bxc5 b6 17. Bd4 Qxc2 18. Rxc2 Bb7 19. f3 Rfc8 20. Rfc1 {1/2-1/2 (30)
Giri,A (2771)-Ivanchuk,V (2738) Leuven 2017}) (4... Nc6 5. dxc5 Qa5+ 6. Bd2
Qxc5 7. Nc3) 5. Nc3 d6 {[%cal Rc8g4,Rb8c6]} (5... Nc6 $6 6. d5 Nd4 7. Bd2 Nxf3+
(7... d6 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Nb5 Qd8 (9... Qb6 $4 10. c5 $1 dxc5 11. Qa4 $18 {
[%cal Gd2a5,Gb5c7]}) 10. Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gb5d4]} a5 11. Ba3 Bd7 (11... Nf6 $2 12.
e5 $1 Ne4 (12... dxe5 13. d6 $18) 13. Qe2 Bf5 14. exd6 O-O 15. dxe7 {1-0 (38)
Kreisl,R (2398)-Brunello,S (2592) Sibenik 2012}) 12. Nxd4 Nf6 13. Qd3 $1 $16 (
13. Bd3 {1-0 (23) Kortschnoj,V (2603)-Malisov,B (2324) Davos 2006})) 8. Qxf3 d6
9. Bd3 Nf6 10. O-O $16 {[%cal Gf3e2,Gf2f4,Ge4e5] 1/2-1/2 (31) Artemiev,V (2703)
-Zvjaginsev,V (2644) Cheliabinsk 2018}) (5... Nf6 6. Bd2 cxd4 7. Nxd4 {the
game resumes to a normal Maroczy Bind and there are no immediate tactics for
Black.} Nxe4 $4 8. Nxe4 Qe5 9. Bd3 Qxd4 10. Bc3) 6. d5 $1 {forcing Black to
take on c3 otherwise nothing makes sense about Black's chosen strategy; and,
what exactly is the black queen doing on a5?} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nf6 (7... Qxc3+ {
choosing a doubled c-pawn over a central pawn doesn't look logical.} 8. Bd2 Qg7
9. Bd3 {the two bishop power, an advantage in development and more space is more
than sufficient for good compensation for the sacrificed pawn. The following
game is not forced.} (9. h3 $5) 9... f6 10. Qc1 g5 11. h4 g4 12. Ng1 Nd7 13.
Ne2 Ne5 14. Bb1 e6 15. a4 f5 16. Ng3 Nf6 17. O-O fxe4 18. Bxe4 exd5 19. Bxd5
Nxd5 20. cxd5 Bd7 21. Bh6 Qe7 22. Re1 O-O-O 23. Bg5 Qf7 24. Rxe5 dxe5 25. Qxc5+
