-Chatalbashev,B (2573) Val Thorens 2007}) 8. Qc2 Nxe4 9. Bd3 {obviously Black
can't take the 2nd pawn on c3 because of some deadly pins.} Nf6 (9... f5 $6 10.
O-O Nd7 11. Bxe4 fxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qe2 $16) 10. O-O O-O 11. Bg5 Nbd7 12.
Rae1 Re8 13. Nd2 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge1e3] a very logical novelty - before
people used to play 13.Nh4 with some sacrificing threats on g6. That would
give Black time to create counterplay on the queenside.} (13. Nh4 b5 $1 14.
cxb5 (14. Bxg6 $5 $146 fxg6 15. Nxg6 Qd8 16. Re3 {[%cal Gf1e1] is very messy
but probably good!}) 14... c4 15. Bxc4 Bb7 $13 {0-1 (18) Anka,E (2462)
-Vesselovsky,S (2420) Trinec 2002}) 13... Qd8 14. f4 Kg7 15. Re3 a6 16. a4 Ng8
17. Nf3 $40 {it doesn't feel that Black has an extra pawn - White is calling
all the shots here.}) 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 {there are some nuances in which
order Black can develop his pieces but essentially the arising positions are
the same.} (4... Nf6 {I hope you are not concerned about the classical Dragon
- it doesn't have a very good reputation and is quite easy to meet. However,
if it does bother you, you can always start with 3.c4 and only then proceed
with d2-d4. It will include several additional lines to know if Black
postpones taking on d4 but White always keeps the upper hand and has several
