1-0 (45) Navara,D (2727)-Plichta,K (2335) Poland 2018}) 14. Qa4 Qxa4 15. Rxa4
Rfc8 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. exd5 Re8 18. Re1 f5 19. Kf1 Kf7 20. b4 Rac8 21. Rc1 e4
22. Be2 Be5 23. g3 Rc7 24. c5 {White's game is very easy and straightforward.}
Rec8 25. Bxd4 $1 Bxd4 26. c6 bxc6 27. b5 c5 28. b6 axb6 29. axb6 Rb7 30. Rxd4
cxd4 31. Rxc8 Rxb6 32. Ke1 g5 33. Bd1 Rb1 34. g4 fxg4 35. Rc4 Kf6 36. Rxd4 Ke5
37. Ra4 h5 38. Kd2 Kxd5 39. Bc2 Rg1 40. Ra5+ Kd4 41. Bb3 e3+ 42. fxe3+ Ke4 43.
Bc2+ Kf3 44. Rf5+ Kg2 45. Rxg5 Kxh2 46. Rxh5+ Kg3 47. Bd1 {1-0 (67) Saric,I 
(2657)-Navara,D (2737) Batumi 2018}) 8. Be2 d6 (8... b6 {[%cal Rc8b7,Re7e6,
Rd7d5] this setup is also quite popular, albeit mostly in accelerated time
controls - if White follows the main and the most tempting line, Black
sacrifices a pawn for a temporary initiative which for blitz and rapid can be
a good strategy. Black's idea is to go for an immediate breakthrough in the
centre. If White is aware of this idea, he should have nothing to be worried
about.} 9. O-O Bb7 10. f3 e6 (10... d6 {if Black switches to the classical
Maroczy Bind, one can question how the bishop is helping Black's cause on b7.
It is very difficult for Black to play the standard b6-b5 idea now and any
d6-d5 counterstrikes in the centre will be too slow. It's a good idea to keep
as many pieces on the board as you can as Black additionally has very little
space for manoeuvres.} 11. Qd2 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf1d1,Gb2b3]} Nd7 {[%cal Rf7f5]
most likely the only reasonable plan Black can think of is to play f7-f5 and
generate some counterplay in the centre. This will seriously weaken his
position and give White easy targets.} 12. Nc2 $1 {as I mentioned before,
Black would love to trade some pieces for more space. Naturally, it's a good
idea not to allow it.} Rc8 13. Rac1 Nc5 14. b3 f5 {and here comes the seek of
counterplay which brings along some weaknesses.} 15. exf5 gxf5 16. f4 $1 Kh8
17. Bf3 e5 18. Nb5 Rf6 19. Rcd1 Qf8 20. Nb4 e4 21. Be2 Nxb4 22. Qxb4 a5 23. Qd2
Rd8 24. Bd4 Rh6 25. Qe3 Bc6 26. Nc3 Rd7 27. Rd2 Bxd4 28. Rxd4 Rg6 29. Rfd1 Qg7
30. Bf1 $16 {1-0 (51) Tomashevsky,E (2695) -Inarkiev,E (2682) Dubai 2014}) 11.
Ndb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5d6] trying to immediately exploit the weakness of the d6
square and practically forcing Black to play d7-d5. While I didn't find a
satisfying game for Black in any line, the position can get a little sharp and
you do have an alternate continuation.} (11. Qd2 {this is a very reasonable
alternative - since Black is willing to go d7-d5, you can prepare and be ready
for it. The queen on d2 additionally protects the bishop on e3 and also allows
to play Rad1 afterwards.} d5 {probably if not now, then never.} (11... Qe7 {
the point of this move is to eliminate the possibility that now after d7-d5
and a couple of exchanges White can't go e4-e5. However, Black can't afford to
be so slow with counterstrikes in the centre.} 12. Ndb5 Ne8 (12... d5 13. cxd5
exd5 14. exd5 Rfd8 15. d6 $16) 13. Rad1 Rd8 14. Kh1 Ba8 15. f4 f5 16. exf5 gxf5
17. Bf3 $16 {0-1 (57) Grigoriants,S (2413)-Shcherbakov,R (2541) Moscow 1999})
12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. e5 $1 {[%csl Rc6,Gd4] White accomplishes a
couple of things with this move - you get a nice outpost on d4 and Black's
light-squared bishop looks really terrible. Plus the d5 pawn is a weakness and
can be targeted.} Ne8 15. f4 f6 {this is the standard counterstrike that Black
usually employs in this line, otherwise he ends up in a strategically lost
position.} 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Rad1 Qe7 18. Bd4 Rad8 19. g3 $1 $146 {the threat
of Nf6-e4 is incoming anyway so White is ready for it and in advance protects
the f4 pawn.} Ne4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Bc4+ Kh8 22. Bxg7+ Kxg7 23. Qc3+ Kh6 (23...
Qf6 24. Qxf6+ Kxf6 25. Kf2 $16 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf2e3]}) 24. Be2 $14 {[%cal
Gg3g5]}) 11... d5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. exd5 Nb4 (13... Ne7 {leads to one long and
forced line which ends with an advantage for White.} 14. d6 Nf5 15. Bf2 Ne8 16.
d7 Nf6 17. g4 $1 Ne7 18. Bh4 a6 19. Qd6 $1 axb5 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Qxf6 b4 22.
Ne4 Bxe4 23. fxe4 Qxd7 24. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Re7,Rf7][%cal Ge4e5,Ge2f3,Ge2c4]
1-0 (32) Kiolbasa,O (2021)-Savant,R (1916) Al Ain 2013}) 14. d6 Nfd5 15. Bf2 $1
{this is the strongest move - Black can enjoy a temporary initiative which
might be important for blitz or rapid games, but normally White should
capitalize on his extra pawn.} a6 (15... Qg5 {[%cal Rd5e3,Rd5f4]} 16. Ne4 Qh6
17. Qb3 $16) (15... Nf4 16. a3 Qg5 17. Bg3 $16) 16. Nc7 $1 Nxc7 17. Bxb6 $1 Be5
(17... Bxc3 18. Bxc7 Qg5 19. bxc3 Nd5 20. Qd4 Nxc7 21. dxc7 $16) 18. dxc7 Qh4 {
the counterattack can look scary but as a matter of fact Black is just losing.}
19. f4 $1 Bxf4 20. Rxf4 $1 Qxf4 21. a3 $18 {White has a winning position.} Qf6
22. Bf2 Nc6 23. Bf3 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc3d5,Ga1c1] 1/2-1/2 (27) Ivkov,B (2540)
-Martin Gonzalez, A Torremolinos 1981}) 9. O-O {This is one of the most popular
positions in the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon line that can occur} Bd7 (9... Nxd4
10. Bxd4 Be6 $6 {the major difference between this line and the main line is
that White hasn't played f2-f3 yet and now he can proceed with the immediate
f2-f4 and win some important tempos because of the f4-f5 threat.} 11. f4 $1 Rc8
12. b3 Qa5 13. Rc1 a6 14. a4 Kh8 15. Kh1 Ng8 16. f5 Bd7 17. Nd5 Bxd4 18. Qxd4+
f6 19. b4 Qd8 20. Nb6 Rc7 21. Rcd1 Qe8 22. a5 Bc6 23. Qe3 Kg7 24. Rc1 Nh6 25.
b5 Bd7 26. bxa6 bxa6 27. c5 Bb5 28. Nd5 Rc8 29. cxd6 Bxe2 30. Qxe2 exd6 31. Nc7
{1-0 (31) Fressinet,L (2718)-Kempinski,R (2615) Germany 2010}) 10. f3 Nxd4 {
Black doesn't have a great choice here.} (10... Qb6 {[%cal Rf6e4]} 11. Na4 Qa5
12. Nb5 Rfc8 (12... a6 $4 13. Bb6 Qb4 14. a3) 13. Rc1 Ne5 14. b3 Bxb5 15. cxb5
$14 {[%csl Ge2,Ge3]}) (10... Rc8 11. Qd2 Ne5 {the setup of the classical
Dragon with the second knight on e5 simply doesn't work here as Black has no
access to the thematic Ne5-c4 move, exchanging one bishop, and it will
inevitably lead to some loss of time after White will prepare h2-h3 and f3-f4.}
12. b3 Qa5 13. Rfd1 a6 14. Rac1 $16 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ge2f1,Gd4e2,Ge2f4,Gf4d5,Gf3f4]
if Black has no access to the b7-b5 thrust, he has no counterplay.}) 11. Bxd4
Bc6 12. Qd2 Nd7 {now let us stop here for a moment - it's important to
understand what Black's strategy is. He wants to trade the dark-squared
bishops and then proceed with the queen trade on b6, thus focusing his game on
White's "bad" bishop on e2. Since Black is lacking space for his pieces, it's
a very reasonable idea to keep as many pieces on the board and make sure Black
has no counterplay.} ({or include} 12... a5 13. b3 {first and then proceed with
} Nd7) 13. Be3 $1 {a paradoxical decision! White keeps the bishops and the
queens on the board and supposedly the black bishop on g7 is very powerful. In
reality, it's doing nothing. White's entire strategy is based on the fact that
he can slowly improve his pieces and Black has problems to create counterplay.
The b7-b5 thrust is not easy to accomplish but f7-f5 creates weaknesses in
Black's camp.} (13. Rac1 Bxd4+ 14. Qxd4 Qb6) (13. Rfd1 Bxd4+ 14. Qxd4 Qb6 15.
Qxb6 Nxb6 $11 {[%csl Re2][%cal Rb6d7,Rd7c5,Re7e5,Rf8d8,Rg8f8,Rf8e7,Rf7f5]})
13... a5 14. b3 {of course, a5-a4 shouldn't be allowed.} Nc5 {[%cal Rd8b6,
Rb6b4,Ra5a4,Rf8c8,Rg7e5,Re7e6,Rd8h4] the critical position of the entire line.
I think Black has two reasonable game-plans that you should be ready for 1)
Play Qb6, Rfc8, Qb4 and prepare the a5-a4 threat, creating a potential
weakness on b3. White's next moves will deal with this threat. 2) Play Be5
with an idea to continue with e7-e6 and bring out the queen to h4, and
possibly continue with f7-f5 or even g6-g5. This will create a weakness on d6
thus will change White's strategy.} (14... a4 $6 15. b4) 15. Rab1 {dealing
directly with the first threat. The strategy may seem weird as you might be
asking - where is White's own game-plan? You will find out that if you deal
with Black's threats first, he will either run out of counterplay or create
weaknesses in his position that you can target. In case the first happens, you
can improve your pieces as long as you want, and eventually prepare a pawn
breakthrough.} Qb6 {[%cal Rb6b4,Ra5a4] the first and original plan} (15... Be5
{the second idea that Black can employ - prepare e7-e6 and try to create
something on the kingside. This does weaken the pawn on d6 and thus the
strategy changes.} 16. Rfd1 {a good preparatory move} e6 {[%cal Rd8e7,Rf7f5]} 17.
Bd4 $5 {Since the situation has changed and Black has created a weakness on d6,
I think it's appropriate that also White can change his strategy and simply
target the weak pawn which involves trading the bishops.} (17. Bf1 $2 {this is
a typical mistake that many people have made here so be careful!} Qh4 18. g3
Qf6 $17 {[%cal Re5c3,Rf6f3]}) 17... Qc7 (17... Qf6 $6 18. Qe3 Rfd8 19. Bxe5 $1
Qxe5 {it may seem that the Black queen is located nicely on e5 but in reality
it's feeling really clumsy there as White will double the rooks on the d-file
and with f2-f4 he will threaten to win the d6 pawn.} 20. Rd2 (20. f4 Qg7 21.
Bf3 {probably was better.} (21. e5 $6 g5 $1 $13 {[%cal Rg7g2]})) 20... g5 21.
Rbd1 Kf8 22. Bf1 $6 (22. Rd4) 22... h6 $6 (22... f5 $1 {[%cal Ge3g5,Re5c3]})
23. g3 Ke7 24. Bg2 b6 25. Kh1 Rd7 26. f4 gxf4 27. gxf4 Qh5 28. Nd5+ Bxd5 29.
exd5 Rg8 30. dxe6 Nxe6 31. Rf1 Qc5 32. Qe1 {1-0 (77) Neiksans,A (2586)-Kveinys,
A (2545) Riga 2017}) 18. Qe3 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd4e5] White is not
interested to take on e5 himself as it will eliminate the weakness on d6 and
give Black a nice control of the d4 and f4 squares. Instead, you can kindly
offer Black to do it himself!} b6 19. Rd2 Rad8 20. Rbd1 $14 {[%cal Ge2f1,Gg2g3,
Gf3f4,Ga2a3,Gb3b4] sooner or later Black will have to take on e5 and then
suffer the consequences of the weak pawn on d6.}) 16. Rfc1 Rfc8 {now Black is
ready to play Qb4 and proceed with a5-a4.} ({or} 16... Qb4 17. Rc2 {and Black
can't rush with a5-a4 because of the Nd5 and the intermezzo Nxe7+ threat.} Rfc8
(17... a4 $2 18. Nd5 Qxd2 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Rxd2 $16) 18. Qc1 {is the same
position, reached with a different order of the moves.}) 17. Rc2 {still
defending against the mentioned threat} Qb4 (17... Qd8 {a standard reaction by
someone who is aware that the Qb4 idea won't work so Black immediately
switches to the idea to trade the dark-squared bishops on h6.} 18. Bf1 h5 19.
a3 {another idea which is not mandatory - White can improve his pieces on the
kingside instead, and leave the queenside closed.} Kh7 20. Kh1 Be5 21. b4 axb4
22. axb4 Ne6 23. Nd5 Ra3 24. f4 Bg7 25. f5 Nf8 26. Bg5 Bxd5 27. Qxd5 e6 28.
fxe6 fxe6 29. Qxb7 Qxg5 30. Qxc8 Qf4 31. Qb7 Kh6 32. g3 Qf3+ 33. Bg2 Qd3 34.
Rbc1 Be5 35. c5 h4 36. gxh4 Qe3 37. Qf7 Nh7 38. h5 gxh5 39. Qxe6+ Nf6 40. Rf1
Ra1 41. Rxa1 Bxa1 42. Qf5 Bd4 43. Qf1 Nxe4 44. Bxe4 Qxe4+ 45. Rg2 dxc5 46. Qf8+
Kh7 47. Qg8+ Kh6 48. Qg5+ {1-0 (48) Carlsen,M (2776)-Lie,K (2539) Gjovik 2009})
18. Qc1 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb3b4] The point of the whole setup! Not only has
White stopped Black's threat of a5-a4, he is threatening to win material with
a2-a3 and b3-b4! Black's forces now have to retreat and this is the moment
when you start to slowly improve your pieces.} Qb6 (18... a4 $4 19. a3) 19. Bf1
h5 (19... f5 $6 {will bring Black only trouble.} 20. exf5 gxf5 21. Nd5 Qd8 22.
Qd2 $16 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gb1e1,Ge3g5]}) 20. g3 {there are plenty of good
improving moves in White's arsenal. Remember - Black has no counterplay.} Kh7 {
[%cal Rb6d8,Rd8f8,Rg7h6] Black is desperately seeking a way to trade the
dark-squared bishops.} 21. Bg2 Qd8 22. Qd2 {continuing to improve.} Qf8 23. Rd1
Bh6 24. f4 $1 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gc3d5] Black has weakened his kingside and White is
ready to tear it apart.}) 5. c4 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gf2f3,Gf1e2,Gc1e3,Ge1g1] And this
is the Maroczy Bind once again - White's pawns e4 and c4 limit Black's active
prospects. I've drawn the next moves you will be making as White - you don't
want to retreat with the knight from d4 but keep it there as long as you can.}
Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 {[%cal Gc1e3,Rf6g4] The most challenging and trickiest setup
Black can put up - he is clearly already eyeing to meet Be3 with Ng4} 7. f3 $1
{I think this is more accurate than 7.Be2 as it stops Black's typical idea
a7-a5-a4 in the end.} (7. Be2 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O {[%cal Rf6g4]} 10.
Qd2 a5 {and White can't meet it with the standard b2-b3 because of the Nxe4
threat.} 11. O-O a4 $1 12. f3 Qa5 {[%cal Rc8e6,Rf6d7,Rd7c5,Ra5b4] and Black
has a reasonably good game. I won't argue that White is still very much fine
and probably even better to some extent but he could have gotten more.}) 7...
Nxd4 (7... Bg7 8. Be3 {effectively transposes to the lines covered earlier.})
8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O {[%cal Rf6g4]} 10. Qd2 {obviously the retreat now is
required as Black was threatening to play Ng4 and exchange that powerful white
bishop on e3.} Be6 {[%cal Rd8a5,Rf8c8] one of the oldest and most popular
responses - Black is going for a quick counterplay against the c4 pawn.} (10...
a5 11. b3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3][%cal Rg7a1] and White manages to play b2-b3 just in
time!} Bd7 (11... a4 $6 12. b4 {typically is not good for Black.}) 12. Be2 Bc6
13. O-O Nd7 {transforms to the lines, covered earlier.}) 11. Rc1 {probably it
