[EventDate "2019.??.??"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {This used to be quite a rare move but thanks to a game of
Carlsen against Grandelius back in 2016 it sparked new interest. However, in
high-level GM games, it is more frequently used in faster time controls and
there are few GMs who dare to play it in a classical game. It's interesting
but still a somewhat dubious continuation as White has a few good
continuations to choose from.} 3. e5 Nd5 4. g3 $5 {And again the same
approach! The general idea is to challenge the position of the black knight on
d5 with the bishop on g2 by executing the d2-d4 push. You can treat the white
bishop on g2 as important as it is in the Catalan or in the Ruy Lopez - in
most of the lines his colleague on c8 will be inferior so Black would be very
happy to trade them. Many lines in this chapter are transpositional to other
chapters.} (4. Nc3 {This is the main continuation and still very good for
White but the game can get quite complex.} Nxc3 {the most popular continuation
at the moment} 5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 Qb6 7. b3 Qc7 8. Qd2 e6 9. h4 h6 10. h5 b6
11. Be2 Bb7 12. c4 {and White is ahead.}) 4... Nc6 (4... e6 {either now or a
move later the game essentially transforms to some of the lines covered in
Chapter 6.}) (4... d6 5. Bg2 {doesn't change much in White's approach as Black
is not ready to immediately take on e5, thus activating White's knight.}) 5.
Bg2 {[%cal Gd2d4] with a direct threat to play d2-d4 on the next move and the
knight on d5 will be hanging.} d6 {a very logical way for Black to proceed
with the development} (5... g6 6. d4 $1 {Black can't be allowed to play Bg7
and d7-d6 while the knight still stands on d5 so you should discard the idea
to play c3 and d4 early - it is in White's best interest to force the knight
to retreat.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nb6 $146 {Usually in this structure the black
knight retreats to c7 but there are always exceptions - this retreat is
interesting. If White will take on c6, Black can consider recapturing with
the d-pawn, aiming for a symmetrical pawn structure.} (7... Nc7 8. Nxc6 bxc6 (
8... dxc6 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Be3 Bg7 11. f4 $14) 9. O-O Bg7 10. Re1 O-O 11. b3 {
[%cal Gc1b2,Gb1c3] with a very easy game for White}) (7... Qa5+ $5 $146 8. Bd2
$1 Qc7 9. Nb5 $1 Qxe5+ 10. Qe2 Qxe2+ 11. Kxe2 a6 12. Nd6+ exd6 13. Bxd5 Bg7 14.
Bc3 $14) 8. Bf4 (8. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 $11 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Nc3 Bf5 {[%csl Rc2] and
Black has a good game}) (8. a4 $5 {I did not analyze this much further but the
continuation definitely deserves some attention!} Bg7 (8... Nxe5 $2 9. a5 Nbc4
10. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Rc4,Re5][%cal Gf2f4,Gb2b3]}) (8... a5 $6 9. f4 Bg7 10. Na3
$1 $14) 9. a5 Nc4 10. Nxc6 bxc6 (10... dxc6 $2 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. f4 $16 {
[%csl Rc4]}) 11. Qe2 Nxa5 (11... Ba6 $5) 12. Bd2 Nb7 13. O-O O-O 14. Bc3 $44 {
with very good compensation and an easy game for White}) 8... Bg7 9. Nxc6 {
Now it's the time to trade the knights!} dxc6 (9... bxc6 10. O-O O-O (10... Nd5
$5 11. Bc1 $5 (11. Bxd5 cxd5 12. Qxd5 Rb8 $13) 11... O-O 12. Re1 d6 13. exd6
Qxd6 {probably with an equal position but chances for both sides}) 11. Re1 $14)
10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nc3 {[%cal Ge1c1] comparing to the previous line by
including Nc3 and Bg7, White has reached a favourable version of the position
and manages to castle long just in time, securing a solid advantage.}) (5...
Nc7 {if the black knight has voluntarily retreated to c7 because of the d2-d4
threat, White should proceed with the c2-c3 and d2-d4 idea which is not so
great if the knight still stands on d5.} 6. O-O g6 7. c3 Bg7 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4
{Black has no choice - he has to push d6 either now or a move later.} d6 (9...
O-O 10. Nc3 d6 11. exd6 exd6 (11... Qxd6 12. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gd4d5]}) 12. Bg5
$14) 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Bf4 Qd8 12. Nc3 {the pawn on d4 is indirectly defended
because of the hanging knight on c7.} Bg4 (12... O-O 13. d5 Nb4 14. d6 $16) (
12... Ne6 $5 13. d5 Nxf4 14. dxc6 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Ne6 16. Rfe1 bxc6 17. Ne5 Rb8
18. Bxc6+ Kf8 19. b3 $14) 13. d5 Nd4 14. Qa4+ Bd7 15. Qb4 $16 {White's
advantage is obvious}) (5... Qc7 $6 {being greedy is not good!} 6. O-O $1 Nxe5
{Of course, Black doesn't have to take on e5 but then the Qc7 move is useless.}
7. Nxe5 Qxe5 8. d4 $1 cxd4 9. Re1 Qd6 10. Qxd4 Qb4 11. Qd1 Nf6 12. a3 Qa5 13.
b4 Qd8 14. c4 e6 15. Nc3 Be7 16. c5 $16 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gc3b5] there's probably
more than one possibility for White to seize the initiative but one thing is
clear - so many extra tempos are definitely worth a pawn!}) 6. exd6 Qxd6 {
the most popular response so far - Black intends to either play e7-e5 or think
about g7-g6 and Bg7, fighting for control in the centre.} (6... Bg4 $5 {
a tricky move, inviting to play a gambit, but White doesn't have to.} 7. h3 $1
(7. dxe7 Qxe7+ 8. Kf1 O-O-O $13 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gd2d3] probably this is playable
for White, at least the computer likes it but it is Black who has the
initiative.}) 7... Bxf3 (7... Bh5 8. d4 $1 $146 {this motif will be available
in many setups - if the black bishop has already been chased to h5, the pawn
on d4 is indirectly defended because of the g3-g4 intermezzo threat and the
knight on d5 can be hanging.} cxd4 (8... Qxd6 9. O-O {continuing the
development and not worrying about the pawn on d4.} cxd4 (9... O-O-O $6 10. c4
Nb6 11. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5] with a strong attack against the exposed Black king.}
) 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxd4 {should be more or less the same as the previous line})
9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxd4 Qxd6 11. O-O e6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. c4 Nb4 14. Nc3 {White has
an edge}) 8. Bxf3 Qxd6 9. Nc3 e6 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. O-O Be7 12. d3 {with a very
simple and pleasant game for White. In the particular game White won in style.}
O-O 13. c3 Rad8 14. Bf4 Qd7 15. Bg2 Bd6 16. Bg5 Be7 17. Bd2 Qf5 18. Qf3 Qg6 19.
Rfe1 Bg5 20. Bxg5 Qxg5 21. h4 Qg6 22. a3 $14 d4 23. c4 Rfe8 24. b4 Rxe1+ 25.
Rxe1 cxb4 26. axb4 Nxb4 27. Qxb7 Qd6 28. Re7 Nxd3 29. Rxf7 Qe5 30. Re7 Qf6 31.
Bd5+ Kh8 32. Rf7 Qe5 33. Qd7 Qb8 34. Qg4 Qe5 35. Qf3 {1-0 (35) Rublevsky,S 
(2702) -Lintchevski,D (2579) St Petersburg 2015}) (6... exd6 7. O-O Be7 8. d4
O-O 9. Re1 Bf6 10. c3 {because of the awkward position of the black knight on
d5 White keeps some advantage.} Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Qb3 Nb6 13. dxc5 dxc5 14.
Na3 $14) (6... e6 {if Black wants to recapture on d6 with the bishop, White
should proceed with the breakthrough in the centre, increasing the power of
the bishop on g2 battery.} 7. d4 Bxd6 8. c4 Nf6 (8... Nb6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10.
Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nbd2 $14) 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nc3 Ke7 12. O-O $14 {
[%csl Rc8,Gg2][%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4] 1/2-1/2 (40) Shabanov,Y (2422)-Losev,D (2345)
Moscow 2007}) 7. O-O {[%cal Gd2d4] White wants to play d2-d4 on the next move
and preferably win some tempos because of the misplaced queen on d6. There
are not many possibilities how Black can counter this.} Bg4 (7... e5 {it's
very tempting for Black to grab the centre but it only creates easy targets
for White.} 8. Re1 {[%cal Gb1a3,Gc2c3,Gd2d4] the idea to play c2-c3 and d2-d4
thus crushing the centre is obvious.} (8. d3 Be7 9. Nbd2 Nb6 10. a4 a6 11. a5
Nd7 12. Nc4 Qc7 13. Re1 O-O 14. c3 Bf6 15. Nfd2 Rb8 16. Nb3 Re8 17. Be3 Ne7 18.
Be4 g6 19. Qe2 Bg7 20. f4 b5 21. axb6 Nxb6 22. Nxb6 Qxb6 23. Nxc5 {1-0 (40)
Dervishi,E (2540)-Afek,Y (2288) Altenkirchen 2012}) 8... Be7 9. Na3 {[%cal
Ga3c4,Ga3b5] provoking Black to play f7-f6 first so that the breakthrough in
the centre comes with even greater power.} f6 (9... Nb6 10. Nb5 $14 {[%cal
Gf3e5,Ga2a4]}) 10. c3 O-O 11. Nc4 Qd8 12. d4 $14) 8. h3 Bxf3 {by doing this
Black stops the d2-d4 threat for good and can resume his development but in
the process White gains a powerful light-squared bishop and a long lasting
pressure.} (8... Bh5 9. d4 $1 {leads to a line, covered earlier.}) 9. Qxf3 e6
10. Na3 (10. Nc3 {also looks normal.} Nf6 11. d3 Be7 12. Re1 O-O 13. a4) 10...
Be7 11. d3 O-O 12. Nc4 Qd7 13. a4 $1 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gf1e1,Gf3g4,Gh3h4] Black is
solid but lacks a clear gameplan. White can organize an attack on the kingside
as shown in the game below.} (13. Re1 Bf6 14. c3 Rad8 15. a4 b6 (15... Nxc3 16.
bxc3 Bxc3 {is something that White always should be ready for - the idea comes
from the Dutch Leningrad system where the position is identical only White's
pawn is on f4 and not on f2.}) 16. h4 h6 17. Qg4 Kh8 18. Qh5 Kg8 19. Be4 Rfe8
20. a5 b5 21. Ne3 b4 22. Ng4 bxc3 23. Bxh6 gxh6 24. Bxd5 Bg7 25. Bxc6 Qxc6 26.
Nxh6+ Bxh6 27. Qxh6 cxb2 28. Rab1 Rxd3 29. Rxb2 {1-0 (55) Demidov,M (2520)
-Grachev,B (2626) St Petersburg 2018}) 13... Bf6 14. c3 $14 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gf3g4,
Gh3h4]} *

