1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {If Black doesn't want to pursue one of the main
lines of this database, he has several less explored continuations at his
disposal. None of them gives Black an equal game so this choice shouldn't be of great concern for White.} b6 {Unlike in the line 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.b3 where
3...b6 actually is one of the best moves, here it is not. Because of it, I
decided to offer to switch to an open Sicilian as there's a good possibility
that Black will have to switch to a bad version of the Hedgehog system and
walk a tightrope not to get into deep trouble immediately. Still, if White is
not in the mood for it, he can always go for a simple kingside attack with Bg2,
Nc3, d3, 0-0, Ng5-h3 followed by f2-f4 and g3-g4. But the main line is so much
better!} (3... a6 {This might be a standard reaction by a player who typically
tries to set up the Paulsen Kan system - Black plans to play b7-b5 and Bb7,
targeting the e4 pawn. For Black there's one serious setback - White has not
yet developed his knight to c3 so it can't be challenged with the later b5-b4,
but the pawn b5 itself can become an easy target with a2-a4. You have several
options here: 1) proceed in the same manner as with 3...b6 and switch to an
open Sicilian with attacking perspectives. According to the engines, this is
the best choice but the game can get really sharp. 2) Play a positional game
and prepare c2-c3 with d2-d4 afterwards - it is very possible that some lines
will be transpositional with the first choice. 3) Choose the King's Indian
attack as described in Chapter 8.} 4. Bg2 {[%cal Gd2d4] It is possible that
here Black has other continuations besides 4...b5 or 4...Nc6. But that would
make the previous move meaningless so you can strive to get a better version
for a line which is covered in other chapters with the inclusion of ...a6. The
ability to compare lines and the arising differences with the inclusion of
certain moves is quite important.} (4. d4 $6 {now is not so good because Black
immediate gets a fine game.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5) 4... b5 (4... Nc6 5. O-O {
most likely will lead to a covered variation with a different order of the
moves.}) 5. O-O (5. d3 Bb7 6. O-O d6 7. Nbd2 Nf6 8. Ng5 Be7 9. f4 {[%cal Gg3g4,
Gg5h3]}) (5. d4 {[%cal Gd2d4] Option number 1: switching to a very good open
Sicilian position - if Black plays everything correctly, you can still
transpose this line to the option 2.} cxd4 (5... Bb7 6. d5 Nf6 7. Nh4 $16) 6.
Nxd4 Bb7 7. O-O Nc6 {Black probably has to play either this or 7... Qc7 to
avoid being slaughtered in the similar manner as analyzed in the main line
with 3...b6.} (7... Nf6 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5] I don't guarantee that I've
gathered all possible continuations from Black but at least you will have a
clearer picture of the typical plans White should be thinking about.} d5 (8...
Nc6 $6 9. e5) (8... Qc7 $6 9. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gc3d5,Ge4e5]} b4 10. Bf4 e5 (
10... d6 11. Nd5 exd5 12. exd5+ Kd8 13. Rc1 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bxd5 15. c4 $18) 11.
Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 d6 13. c3 bxc3 14. Rc1 $18) (8... Bc5 9. Nb3 Be7 10. e5 Nd5
11. Qg4 Kf8 {[%cal Rh7h4]} 12. Qh5 $1 $16) (8... h5 9. e5 (9. a4 $5) 9... Bxg2
10. exf6 Bb7 11. fxg7 Bxg7 12. Nf5 $16) (8... d6 9. e5 (9. a4 b4 10. Bg5 $16 {
[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Ge4e5]}) 9... Bxg2 10. exf6 Bb7 11. Bg5 {[%cal Gd4e6]} Qd7
12. fxg7 Bxg7 13. Nf5 $13) 9. e5 Nfd7 10. Nd2 Be7 11. Qg4 O-O 12. N2f3 $14) (
7... Qc7 8. Re1 Nc6 9. c3 {in the same manner} Be7 10. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gd1g4]}
) 8. c3 $5 {a very simple continuation, promising a good game for White.
You're aiming to recapture on d4 with the pawn, and the position could
transform into a typical French defence position. As soon as Black will
develop his knight on f6, think about e4-e5 and Qd1-g4.} Nxd4 9. cxd4 Nf6 10.
Re1 d5 11. e5 Nd7 12. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gd1g4,Gb1c3,Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gf4h5]}) 5... Bb7
6. Re1 {the second option - take control of the center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.
This approach is more positional and more in the spirit of the Anti-Sicilian
approach thus my favourite.} (6. d3 {the third option - of course, you can
still proceed with the classical King's Indian Attack - White's moves are
standard and Black has to figure it out, how to properly defend against the
kingside attack. You can find some details in Chapter 8 as an alternative
continuation.} d6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Nd2 (8. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5h3,Gf2f4,Gg3g4]}) 8...
Nc6 9. f4 Be7 10. g4) 6... Nc6 (6... Nf6 7. e5 Nd5 8. d3 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4,
Gb1c3,Gc1f4]}) 7. c3 Nf6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gd1g4] I like this
continuation more as it comes with a direct threat of e4-e5 and Qd1-g4.} (9.
cxd4 d5 10. e5 {probably also is good}) 9... Nxd4 10. cxd4 d5 11. e5 Nd7 12.
Be3 $14 {[%cal Gd1g4,Gb1c3,Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gf4h5]}) (3... d6 4. Bg2 Nf6 {would be
an odd way to switch to the main lines after} 5. Nc3 {covered in Chapter 8, or
5.Qe2 analyzed in Chapter 9. However, White can also simply proceed with an
immediate pawn thrust in the centre, granting him a stable plus.} (5. e5 $5
dxe5 6. Nxe5 {[%csl Gg2]} Bd6 (6... Nbd7 7. Nc4 $146 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. a4 Nb6
10. d3 $14) 7. Nc4 Bc7 8. b3 O-O 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. O-O Rb8 11. a4 $14 {1-0 (32)
Frostick,C (2133)-Marwitz,T (2031) Dresden 2018})) (3... Nf6 {will be analyzed
in Chapter 6.}) (3... g6 {a very early attempt to switch to a closed Sicilian
or French won't work as White can and should proceed with d2-d4 in one go.} 4.
d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 $1 (5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Bg2 {[%cal Gb1c3,Ge1g1] is also very good
for White}) 5... Nf6 $146 (5... Qf6 $6 6. Qd1 Nc6 7. Bg2 $16 Bh6 8. Nc3 Bxc1 9.
Qxc1 a6 10. Qe3 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. O-O-O Nf6 13. f4 Qa5 14. Qd4 Qd8 15. e5
Nh5 16. g4 Ng7 17. Ne4 O-O 18. Nf6+ Kh8 19. h4 {1-0 (27) Bekker Jensen,D (2289)
-Pedersen,H (2171) Koge 2014}) 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Nc3 h6 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. e5 Nc6 10.
Qe3 Bg7 11. Nb5 O-O 12. O-O-O $14 {[%cal Gh2h5,Gb5d6]}) 4. d4 $1 {If Black is
ready to play a worse version of the Hedgehog, I see no good reason to avoid
it.} cxd4 (4... Bb7 {is playable but now White can immediately shut out the
bishop from the business.} 5. d5 $1 Nf6 6. Nc3 exd5 7. exd5 Be7 8. Bg2 d6 9. O-O
O-O 10. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gd2c4] White has a solid space advantage and
better piece coordination.}) 5. Nxd4 Bb7 (5... d5 $2 {if Black had played 3...
a6 4. d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4, this manoeuvre would have given him a very good game. Here
it's a bad mistake.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. exd5 $16) 6. Bg2 Nf6 (6... Nc6 7. Nb5 {
[%cal Gb5d6] this manoeuvre is common in the Sicilian Sveshnikov - White wants
to occupy the weak d6 square and gain the two bishop advantage.} d6 8. Bf4 e5 (
8... Ne5 $6 9. Qd4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gb5d6]}) 9. Be3 a6 10. N5c3 Nf6 11. Nd2 $14 {
feels like a terrible version of the Sicilian Sveshnikov for Black.}) 7. Nc3 {
so far these moves could have been made automatically as they make the most sense.
Now Black has to be very accurate.} Nc6 $146 {perhaps the best chance for
Black is to try to escape the looming trouble if he's actually aware of it!
In most cases Black probably will be totally oblivious here what's waiting for
him, otherwise he wouldn't have had entered this line.} (7... a6 $6 {either
with this or 7...d6 Black can try to setup the Hedgehog system but clearly not
in the most optimal order as White will very quickly proceed with the thematic
Re1 and Nd5 or Nf5 ideas, with e4-e5 threat as an additional resource to slow
down Black's positibilities to finish the development.} 8. O-O d6 9. Re1 {
[%cal Ge4e5,Gd4f5,Gc3d5] e4-e5 already is a big threat so Black has no time to
play Be7. Additionally Nc3-d5 and Nd4-f5 are very serious threats as well.} Qc7
(9... Be7 $4 10. e5 dxe5 11. Bxb7 Ra7 12. Bc6+ $18) (9... Nbd7 $2 10. e5 Bxg2
11. exf6 Bb7 12. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 13. Rxe6+ Kf7 14. fxg7 Bxg7 15. Rxd6 $18 {
[%csl Rd7,Rf7]}) (9... Qc8 10. Nd5 Nbd7 11. Bg5 $16 h6 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Bh3 h5
14. Re3 {[%cal Ge3c3,Ge3f3]} Rg8 15. Bxe6 {[%cal Gd1h5]} (15. Rf3 $2 {1-0 (20)
Inkiov,V (2500)-Barczay,L (2400) Paris 1996}) 15... fxe6 16. Qxh5+) 10. Nd5 $1
{It may seem that this is a fantastic sacrifice but the motif is really common
in the Sicilian.} exd5 (10... Nxd5 11. exd5 e5 {doesn't save Black's position
either} 12. f4 (12. Re3 $5 $146 {[%cal Ge3c3]} Be7 13. Rc3 {[%cal Gd4c6,Gd4e6]}
Qd8 14. Nc6 Qd7 15. Be3 Bd8 16. f4 $18) 12... Nd7 13. fxe5 Nxe5 14. Bf4 Be7 15.
Nf5 Bf6 16. Nxd6+ Qxd6 17. Qd4 O-O 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 19. Rxe5 $16 {0-1 (59)
Safarli,E (2639) -Ponkratov,P (2613) Riadh 2017}) 11. exd5+ Kd8 (11... Be7 $4
12. Nf5 {is just game over}) 12. Bg5 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge2e8]} Nbd7 13. Qe2 $16 Kc8
(13... Qc5 14. Nc6+ Kc7 15. Be3 Re8 16. Qd2 Qc4 17. b3 Qg4 18. a4 {with a
