1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 Nf6 {Black plays in the spirit of the Alapin
variation, where 2.c3 or 3.c3 is met by Nf6. However, here White will find the
inclusion of 3.g3 to be more useful.} 4. e5 $1 Nd5 5. Bg2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d4]
Comparing with the Alapin, White didn't even need to go c2-c3 and he can
proceed with the immediate d2-d4, and the light-squared bishop is much better
positioned on g2.} Nc6 (5... d6 6. O-O dxe5 (6... Nc6 7. d4 {transpositions to
the main line}) 7. Nxe5 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1 $14 Nxc3 10. dxc3 $1 {I believe
that in similar positions taking on c3 with the d-pawn is a much simpler
choice.}) (5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. d4 {essentially transforms to one of the
lines covered in different variations.}) 6. O-O d6 (6... Be7 7. Re1 O-O (7...
f6 $6 $146 {Probably Black might be thinking about making this thrust sooner
or later to generate some play on the f-file once castled, but it never really
works as Black is behind in development.} 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. dxc3 O-O 10. exf6 Bxf6
11. Bf4 d5 12. Qd2 h6 13. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Re6]}) 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 (
9... f6 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. Nf5 Nde7 12. Nxe7+ Bxe7 13. Be3 d5 14. c3 $14 {
[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf2f4,Gb1d2,Gd2f3]}) 10. Qxd4 d6 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. c4 Nb4
13. Qxd6 Bxd6 14. Na3 $14 (14. Re2 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc1e3]})) (6... g5 $6 $146 {
[%cal Rf8g7,Rd5e7,Re7g6,Rg5g4]} 7. Re1 g4 8. Nh4 h5 9. d3 $16 {[%cal Gg2d5,
Gh4f5]}) 7. d4 $1 {[%cal Gg2a8] the position inevitably will open and Black
will feel the increasing power of the g2 bishop and will have some problems to
finish the development.} cxd4 (7... dxe5 8. dxe5 {[%csl Rc8,Rd6][%cal Gc2c4,
Gb1c3,Gd1e2,Gf1d1]} b5 {otherwise the eventual c2-c4 can seriously damage
Black's position} (8... Be7 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Rd1 Qc7 11. c4 Nb6 12. Nc3 a6 13.
Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gc3e4,Ge4d6,Gh2h4,Gh4h5]}) 9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. Qxd8+ Nxd8 11. bxc3
Bb7 12. Be3 Be7 13. Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Re8g8,Gd1d7]}) 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Nxd4 Nxd4
10. Qxd4 O-O 11. c4 {from here the game is less forced - White enjoys some
space advantage and has a very powerful light-squared bishop.} Qb6 12. Qd3 Nb4
13. Qb3 e5 (13... Bc5 14. Nc3 Bd7 15. a3 Nc6 16. Qxb6 Bxb6 17. b4 {[%cal Gc1b2,
Gc4c5] with some advantage for White.}) 14. Nc3 Be6 15. Be3 Qa6 16. Rfd1 (16.
Nb5 $6 Qxb5 17. cxb5 Bxb3 18. axb3 Nc2 19. Rac1 Nxe3 20. fxe3 Rad8 21. Bxb7 Bb4
22. e4 Ba5 23. Bd5 Bb6+ $11 {1/2-1/2 (56) Leon Hoyos,M (2556)-Neiksans,A (2485)
Balaguer 2010}) 16... Rac8 17. Bf1 Rfd8 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. cxd5 $16 *

