1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5 {a very direct way to counter White's approach and
fight for the centre. Although very tempting, it is not necessarily the best
move for Black.} 4. exd5 exd5 (4... Qxd5 {is possible but it doesn't really
make sense for Black to give up a tempo just like that.} 5. Nc3 Qd8 {the queen
can retreat to different squares as well - so not always will the following
setup work, so be careful.} 6. d4 (6. Bg2 Nc6 7. d3 Nf6 8. O-O Be7 9. Nd2 O-O
10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Bd2 $14 {also is good for White}) 6... Nf6 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. Be3
Ng4 9. Qd2 $5 $146 cxd4 (9... Nxe3 10. Qxe3 $1 cxd4 11. Nxd4 $1 {transforms to
a line, covered later}) 10. Nxd4 Nxe3 11. Qxe3 $3 {the whole point of this
setup!} Nxd4 12. O-O-O Be7 (12... Bc5 $6 13. Qe5 {[%cal Ge5c5,Ge5g7]} Qe7 14.
Qxg7 Rf8 15. Rxd4 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 $16 {[%csl Re8]}) (12... Qb6 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 14.
Rxd4 Bc5 15. Rd2 $14 {[%cal Gc3e4,Ge4d6]}) 13. Rxd4 Qa5 (13... Qc7 $6 14. Rhd1
O-O 15. R4d3 a6 16. Na4 {[%cal Ga4b6]} Qa5 17. b3 $16) 14. Rhd1 O-O 15. R4d3
Rb8 16. Kb1 $14 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gc3e4,Ge4d6]}) 5. d4 {Let us stop here for a
moment. As far as I treat this position, for Black, it's going to be very
difficult to avoid a game with an isolated pawn on d5. If he will try to
release the tension in the centre by playing c5-c4, this will give White a
very nice outpost on e5 for his knight and possibilities to break Black's pawn
structure with a timely b2-b3, then axb3 and possibly c2-c4, winning the
battle for the centre. Black would love to recapture the pawn on c5 in one go
- Bf8xc5 - this is the reason why you should delay the capture on c5 until the
moment when Black will move his bishop from f8, thus winning an important
tempo. Comparing this position to a typical French defence structure (1.e4 e6
2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 c5 4.exd5 exd5), White's king is going to feel more secure on
the kingside as Black will lack the typical counterplay of Bg4 -> Bd6-c7 ->
Qd6 and target h2.} Nf6 {I'm sure there are several ways Black can play here but most of them will lead to the same position in the end.} (5... Nc6 6.
Bg2 Bg4 {This is quite a popular attempt to force White to take on c5 and save
a tempo for the dark-squared bishop to recapture the c5 pawn in one go.} (6...
cxd4 {capturing on d4 for Black doesn't look very appealing right now.} 7. Nxd4
Nf6 (7... Bc5 {I think this is quite a risky choice for Black but perhaps with
very accurate play it's still playable. Now the pawn on d5 becomes unprotected.
} 8. Nb3 {[%csl Rd5]} Qe7+ (8... Bb6 9. O-O $14 {[%cal Gb1c3] the d5 pawn
isn't going anywhere}) 9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 Bb6 11. Nc3 (11. Bxd5 $2 Nb4 12.
Be4 Nf6 $17) 11... Bg4+ (11... Nge7 $5 12. Bxd5 {and Black has to prove if he
has enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. For example,} Nb4 13. Be4 f5
14. Bd3 Nxd3 15. cxd3 O-O 16. Be3) 12. Bf3 Bxf3+ 13. Kxf3 $14 Nb4 $6 14. Bf4 $1
Nxc2 15. Rac1 Nb4 16. Rhe1+ {[%csl Re8]} Kd8 17. Rcd1 Nf6 18. Be5 $16 {[%cal
Ga2a3,Ge5f6,Gd1d5]}) 8. O-O {and Black doesn't have the time to position the
bishop on c5 because of Re1+.} Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Re1 {the biggest difference
between this line and the main line is that Black took on d4 himself and the
bishop is in a slightly more passive position on e7. Thus the a3 move no
longer is really needed as there's none to be bothered on the c5 square.} Bg4
11. Qd3 Nb4 12. Qb5 Bd7 13. Qe2 Re8 14. Be3 $14) (6... Qe7+ $6 7. Be3 {The
early frontal check just looks terrible for Black, as long as White has access
to the Be3 move.}) (6... Nf6 {transforms to the main line}) 7. O-O $1 {Of
course! The only way to fight for an advantage involves a pawn sacrifice,
although temporary.} cxd4 {this is the main move here and so far Black's been
doing quite well. Here I will offer you a choice - either go to a known
endgame where White is pushing but objectively it's a draw, or pursue a
complex game.} (7... Nxd4 8. Qe1+ Be7 (8... Ne6 $6 9. Ne5 Bf5 10. c4 $16 {
[%cal Gg2a8] and Black is in trouble}) 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Qe5 $1 {[%cal Ge5d4,
Ge5g7] a standard idea for this line to recapture the pawn immediately.} Nf6
11. Qxd4 O-O 12. Nc3 $14) (7... Nf6 {comparing to the main lines of the
Chapter 8, White has managed here to make a short castle instead of Nc3 which
is even better.} 8. Re1+ Be7 9. dxc5 O-O 10. h3 Bh5 (10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Bxc5
12. Nc3 d4 13. Ne2 $14) 11. g4 Bg6 12. Be3 Ne4 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Be4 15.
Nd4 $16) 8. Nbd2 $5 {My suggested continuation which I find to be more
interesting and dynamic than the dry endgame which ensues after the much more
popular 8.h3. However, the choice is up to you!} (8. h3 {leads to a forced
line which has been employed by some world class GMs as Anand, Nakamura,
Morozevich, Artemiev and others. I'm a bit puzzled what they find so appealing
about this line!} Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nf6 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Re1+ Ne7 13.
Qxd5 Qxd5 14. Bxd5 O-O (14... d3 $6 {flashy but not good enough.} 15. Nc3 dxc2
(15... d2 16. Re3 $1 Rd8 17. Bf3 O-O 18. Rd1 $14 {and the brave Black pawn
should fall.}) (15... O-O-O 16. Bxf7 Bxc3 17. bxc3 d2 18. Red1 $16) 16. Rac1
O-O 17. Rxc2 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Bd8 19. a4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (76) Morozevich,A (2758)
-Vitiugov,N (2691) Eilat 2012}) 15. Be4 Rac8 {although White has a nominal
plus, it can be difficult to convert it to a win.} 16. Nd2 Rfd8 17. Rad1 g6 18.
Re2 Nc6 19. Nf3 b6 20. Kf1 Na5 21. Bd3 Nc4 22. Bxc4 Rxc4 {½-½ (75) Artemiev,
V (2709)-Perunovic,M (2597) Skopje 2018. White hopes to outplay Black in the
endgame due to the good knight versus the bad bishop. The position is simply
equal.}) 8... Bc5 {Black can try to keep the pawn for the time being but by
doing so he has to position his pieces in awkward positions and give up the
light-squared bishop. In my opinion, it's a good price for temporary pawn
sacrifice.} (8... Nf6 9. Nb3 {doesn't pose any problems for White - Black
can't really hold the pawn or he will run into trouble.} Be7 (9... Bxf3 $6 10.
Bxf3 Qb6 11. a4 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ga1a4] a very logical novelty - White
wants to chase away the queen from b6 and possibly also include Ra4 to target
the d4 pawn.} (11. Bg5 {1/2-1/2 (37) McShane,L (2670)-Perunovic,M (2620)
Hungary 2015}) 11... Be7 (11... a5 {stops the a4-a5 and Ra4 manoeuvre, but
seriously weakens the b5 square.} 12. Qe2+ Be7 13. Qb5 Qxb5 14. axb5 Ne5 15.
Bg2 $16) (11... a6 12. a5 Qa7 13. Ra4 $1 $16) (11... Bb4 12. a5 $1 Qc7 (12...
Bxa5 $4 13. Nxa5 Nxa5 14. Qe1+ $18 {[%cal Ge1e8,Ge1a5]}) (12... Nxa5 $4 13.
Nxa5 Bxa5 14. c3 $18 {[%cal Gd1a4,Gb2b4]}) 13. Nxd4 $16 {[%cal Gd4f5,Gc1g5]})
12. a5 Qb4 13. Bd2 Qd6 14. a6 b6 15. Bf4 $14 Qb4 $4 16. c3 $18 {[%csl Rc6]
[%cal Gf3e2,Ge2b5,Ga1c1]}) 10. Nbxd4 O-O 11. c3 Bc5 12. Qa4 {and White
definitely has an edge here.}) (8... Qb6 9. Re1+ Be7 10. h3 Bxf3 (10... Bh5 $6
11. g4 Bg6 12. Nb3 $16) 11. Nxf3 Nf6 12. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Ge1e8]}) (8... Be7 $5 {
[%cal Re7f6,Rg8e7] a tricky move - Black intends to defend the d4 pawn with
the bishop from the more active f6 square.} 9. Re1 {it makes sense to stop
Black's idea right here!} Nf6 10. h3 $1 {I think this is a very important
intermezzo move - it is in White's best interest to move the black bishop a
bit further so that it can't be brought back to the queenside if necessary.}
Bh5 (10... Bxf3 11. Nxf3 Qb6 12. Ne5 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge1e8] this idea must have
been already mentioned somewhere in this chapter but with a different order of
the moves.}) 11. Nb3 O-O 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Rc8 14. Qxa7 $1 $146 {My
suggested improvement which appears to be a novelty.} (14. Be3 Bc5 15. Qd2 Ne4
16. Qd3 Qb6 17. Bxc5 Rxc5 18. Nd4 $11 Qxb2 $6 19. Reb1 Qc3 20. Qxc3 Nxc3 21.
Rxb7 $14 {1-0 (40) Adams,M (2753)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2742) Bilbao 2013}) 14...
Rxc2 15. Be3 Rxb2 (15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Qd7 17. Kg2 Rxb2 18. Rab1 $16 {
essentially is the same}) 16. Rab1 $14 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Rg4c8,Gh2h3] and now
the point is revealed why it was important to include 10.h3 - Black no longer
has access to the defensive resource Bc8!}) 9. Nb3 Bb6 (9... b6 $146 10. Qd3
Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nge7 12. Bf4 O-O 13. a3 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ga1d1,Gb3c1,Gc1d3] and
White's pieces are positioned better - the lost doubled pawn on d4 doesn't
really matter and possibly will be regained later if necessary. White's game
is very easy and straightforward.}) 10. Re1+ $146 Nge7 11. a4 {the following
lines are not forced and should be tested more thoroughly in practice. White's
plan in most of the occasions remains the same - secure the two bishop
advantage and reroute the knight from b3 to d3. The objective evaluation of
the position probably is equal but there's plenty of ways to outplay your
opponent.} O-O (11... a6 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 O-O 14. Bd2 {[%cal Gb3c1,Gc1d3,
Ga4a5,Gb3c5,Gc5d3] White is pressing and has very good compensation for the
sacrificed pawn.}) (11... a5 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 O-O 14. Bd2 {[%cal Gb3c1,
Gc1d3,Ga1d1] the plan remains the same as with 11...a6}) 12. a5 Bc7 (12... Nxa5
$2 13. Nxa5 Bxa5 14. Rxe7 Qxe7 15. Rxa5 $16) 13. h3 (13. a6 Bb6 $1 14. axb7 Rb8
$11) 13... Bxf3 (13... Bh5 14. a6 Bxf3 (14... Bb6 $6 15. axb7 Rb8 16. g4 Bg6
17. Nfxd4 $16) 15. Bxf3 Bb6 16. Bg5 f6 17. axb7 Rb8 18. Bf4 Rxb7 19. Nc1 $13)
14. Qxf3 Re8 15. Bd2 Ne5 16. Qd1 {For the sacrificed pawn White enjoys the two
bishop advantage and for Black, it can be difficult to keep the pawn in the
long term.} d3 17. Bc3 dxc2 18. Qxc2 N5c6 19. Qd2 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge1e2,
Ga1e1,Gb3c5]}) 6. Bg2 Be7 (6... Qe7+ $2 {although this move has been played
even at GM level, it's a bad continuation and brings Black only trouble.} 7.
Be3 Ng4 8. O-O {a very natural pawn sacrifice which Black can't accept.} Nxe3
9. fxe3 Nc6 ({obviously not} 9... Qxe3+ $2 10. Kh1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gf1e1]} Be6
11. c4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gf1e1]}) 10. c4 $1 dxc4 11. d5 $1 {I find this
continuation to be the most straightforward which secures a big advantage for
White} Ne5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Na3 Bd6 (13... Qb8 $4 14. Nxc4 (14. Qf3 $1 $18 {
[%csl Rf7]}) 14... Bd6 15. Qa4+ Bd7 16. Nxd6+ Qxd6 17. Qe4+ Kf8 18. Qf4 Qxf4
19. gxf4 Re8 20. e4 $16 {1/2-1/2 (30) Martynov,P (2385)-Krejci,J (2500)
Pardubice 2015}) 14. Nxc4 Qe7 15. e4 Be5 (15... O-O $4 16. e5 Bxe5 17. d6 Qg5
18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. d7 $18) 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb2b4,
Gc2c5] and Black should give up the pawn to avoid even greater problems. For
