Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nc3 O-O 10. a3 {essentially is the same as the main line})
7. O-O O-O (7... c4 8. Ne5 O-O 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 Nc6 11. c4 Be6 12. Nc3 Bb4
13. Ne2 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ge2f4] looks rather bleak for Black.}) 8. dxc5 {
now it's the time to take the pawn - Black has lost a tempo with the maneuver
Bf8-e7xc5.} Bxc5 9. Nc3 Nc6 (9... h6 {Black postpones developing his queenside
knight to c6 to secure his dark-squared bishop's position first. White's plan
remains the same.} 10. a3 a6 (10... Nc6 11. b4 {transforms to the main lines})
11. b4 Ba7 12. Bb2 Nc6 13. Ne2 Re8 14. Nf4 {[%cal Gb2f6,Gf4d5]} d4 15. Qd3 $14
{[%csl Rd4][%cal Ga1d1,Gd3b3,Gf3d4,Gc2c4,Gc4c5] White is clearly is the
driver's seat.}) 10. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1g5,Gc1b2,Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gd1d3] a very
clever and multi purpose move! White intends to play b2-b4 and either proceed
with the standard idea Bg5 and after the exchange win the pawn on d5 (the
b-pawn is no longer on b2 after Qxf6) or fianchetto the bishop on b2, making a
pair of deadly bishops. After that White typically proceeds with Qd3, Ne2-f4
and makes the d5 pawn feel really uncomfortable.} ({the straightforward} 10.
Bg5 {is not so clear} Be6 11. Bxf6 ({and now trying to reach the same position
with a different order of the moves doesn't work anymore} 11. a3 h6 12. Bxf6
Qxf6 {White can't play b2-b4 and Nxd5 because it's hanging on c3.}) 11... Qxf6
12. Nxd5 Qxb2) 10... Bg4 $5 $146 {I've come to a conclusion that this logical
novelty probably is the best defensive setup for Black, fighting for equality.
Black wants to provoke h2-h3 so that he can retreat with the bishop to e6 and
essentially win a tempo by playing Qd7, targeting the h3 pawn.} (10... a6 11.
b4 Ba7 12. Bg5 Be6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Rad8 16. Qb3 $16 {
1-0 (26) Zvjaginsev,V (2644)-Yudin,S (2525) Chelyabinsk 2018}) (10... Re8 $5 {
has been played already twice between GMs Zviaginsev and Rublevsky but Black
is struggling in all lines - I found two novelties which secure White a solid
advantage.} 11. b4 Bb6 12. Bg5 d4 {and now White has a pleasant choice} 13.
Bxf6 (13. Na4 $146 {is a reasonable alternative to consider} Bc7 14. Re1 Rxe1+
15. Qxe1 Bg4 16. b5 $14) 13... Qxf6 14. Nd5 Qd8 15. Re1 $5 $146 (15. Nd2 Be6
16. Nf4 Bf5 17. Nd3 Qc7 18. Qf3 Bg6 19. Rfe1 Rac8 20. Nc4 Nxb4 21. Nxb4 Qxc4
22. Qxb7 Qc3 23. Bf1 Be4 24. Rxe4 Qxa1 25. Kg2 Qxa3 26. Bc4 Kh8 27. Bxf7 Rf8
28. Rh4 Rce8 29. Qd7 g6 30. Bxe8 Rxf2+ 31. Kh3 h5 32. Bxg6 Qxb4 33. Qh7# {
