1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 Nc6 4. Bg2 Nf6 {Finally we've come to the most
popular move order - Black develops both of his knights first and wants to see
what exactly White has in his mind. I have decided to offer you a choice -
there are two very good continuations you can choose from, both promise White
a good game, although not always with an advantage. In this Chapter, I will
cover everything related 5.Nc3 - if you find it good enough, you can even skip
 Chapter 9 which will concentrate on 5.Qe2. My goal was to offer to you a
few choices as rarely everyone has the same taste.} (4... Nge7 $6 {not a good
setup for Black.} 5. O-O d5 (5... g6 {this concept would be great for Black if
White had already played d2-d3 before, aiming for a closed Sicilian or French
structure. Now White easily gets a stable advantage.} 6. d4 $1 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Bg7
8. Nxc6 $1 (8. Nb5 $6 {this tempting move actually gives away all the
advantage.} d5 9. exd5 exd5 10. Bf4 O-O 11. N1c3 Be6 12. Nc7 Rc8 13. Nxe6 fxe6
14. Re1 Qd7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (46) Hovhannisyan,R (2591)-Vazquez,G (2374) Doha 2014}
) 8... bxc6 (8... Nxc6 9. Na3 O-O 10. c3 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 9. Qd6 {otherwise
Black can play d7-d5 too easily.} Qa5 10. Rd1 $1 (10. Nd2 {1/2-1/2 (32)
Hasangatin, R (2505)-Kulkarni, R (2296) Pardubice 2016}) 10... Be5 11. Qd2 (11.
Bd2 $1 Qb5 12. Nc3 $3 Bxd6 13. Nxb5 Bxg3 14. hxg3 cxb5 15. Bc3 O-O 16. e5 Nc6
17. Bb4 Re8 18. Bc5 $16 {is the engine's choice}) 11... Qxd2 12. Nxd2 d5 13.
Nb3 $14) 6. exd5 Nxd5 (6... Qxd5 $6 7. c3 Qd3 8. Na3 Nf5 9. Qc2 Qxc2 10. Nxc2
Be7 11. d4 cxd4 12. Ncxd4 Nfxd4 13. Nxd4 Bd7 14. Be3 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bf6 16. Bxb7
Rb8 17. Bxf6 (17. Bf3 {1-0 (48) Chadaev,N (2582)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2646)
Moscow 2013}) 17... gxf6 18. Ba6 Rb6 19. Bd3 Rxb2 20. Rab1 Rb6 21. Rxb6 axb6
22. Rb1 Ke7 23. Rxb6 $16) 7. d4 Be7 (7... Nf6 8. Ne5 $1 Bd7 (8... Nxd4 $4 9. c3
Nc6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nxf7+ $18) 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. dxc5 Qxd1 11.
Rxd1 Bxc5 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Na4 Be7 14. c4 (14. Be3 {1-0 (44) Balague Camps,M 
(2180)-Baches Garcia,G (2311) Barcelona 2017}) 14... Rfd8 15. Be3 $14) 8. dxc5
O-O 9. Qe2 Bxc5 10. Rd1 Qe7 11. c4 Nf6 12. Nc3 h6 13. a3 $1 Rd8 (13... a5 14.
Na4 {[%csl Rb6]}) 14. Rxd8+ Qxd8 15. Bf4 Qe7 16. b4 e5 17. bxc5 exf4 18. Qxe7
Nxe7 19. Ne5 fxg3 20. hxg3 $16 {1/2-1/2 (65) Khatanbaatar,B (2345)-Munguntuul,
B (2428) Ulaanbaatar 2016}) (4... g6 $6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qb6 7. Nb3 (7. Nxc6
bxc6 8. Be3 Qc7 9. O-O Bg7 10. Bc5 d5 11. Nd2 Nf6 12. Re1 Bf8 13. Bxf8 Kxf8 14.
c4 $16 {0-1 (49) Carlsen,M (2837)-Svidler,P (2749) Astana 2012}) 7... Bg7 8.
O-O Nge7 9. Na3 $1 $16 {[%cal Ga3c4,Gc4d6,Gc2c4]}) 5. Nc3 $5 d5 (5... a6 $6 {
doesn't contribute anything for Black and apart from the obvious d2-d4 push in
the centre White can now safely go to the King's Indian attack with an extra
tempo.} 6. O-O d6 7. d3 Be7 8. Ng5 (8. Nd2 $5) 8... h6 9. Nh3 Qc7 10. f4 O-O
11. g4) (5... d6 6. O-O Be7 {this is the critical moment of the whole system
with 5.Nc3 and that is why I was having my doubts whether I should offer this
as your main line or not. Here the most sensible move is to go 7.d4 which is
also the continuation of one of the experts of this line, Lu Shanglei. By
doing this you have avoided many theoretical lines and White has an easy game.
But it still remains a mainstream Sicilian theory and my goal was to offer you interesting alternatives. So it remains up to you if at this moment you
want to switch to an open Sicilian, or pursue a typical King's Indian attack
on the kingside.} 7. d3 (7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 O-O 9. a4 {[%cal Gd4b3,Gc1e3,Gd1e2,
Ga1d1] is entirely possible and quite good for White but I won't analyze it
here.}) 7... O-O {from here White can pursue two ways for a typical kingside
attack - the ideas are very similar. The only difference is that with 8.Ng5
White in certain lines allow Black to trade queens early - if he doesn't go
for it, White will have a very good King's Indian attack. With 8.Nd2 White
keeps queens on the board but the 2nd knight often can't make it to the
kingside and will have to protect the queenside via a3 instead. Be advised -
engines don't really like White's position most of the times which applies for
King's Indian openings as well. However, White at all times has an easy game
plan - attack the black king and march forward on the kingside with everything
he has got. My goal is not to provide to you exact moves by moves, but more
typical ideas which you might find useful.} 8. Ng5 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg5h3]
perhaps the easiest choice as it quite automatically provokes Black to play
h7-h6 which might become a target in a later attack.} (8. Nd2 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4,
Gg3g4] the second alternative which allows White to keep the queens on the
board if Black is looking for ways to simplify the position, or at least trade
them in a better moment.} d5 $1 {I think Black has to do it immediately
otherwise White will start the assault with the instant g3-g4.} (8... e5 9. Nc4
{[%cal Gf2f5] transfers to one of the lines I covered earlier.}) (8... Rb8 {
allows the immediate} 9. g4 $5 $146 (9. f4 d5 10. e5 (10. g4 d4 11. Ncb1 e5 12.
f5 h6 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Gf6h7,Ge7g5]}) 10... Nd7 11. Nf3 b5 12. Ne2 d4 13. g4 f6
14. a4 a6 15. axb5 axb5 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. h3 $15 {1/2-1/2 (17) Piorun,K (2634)
-Babula,V (2538) Slovakia 2019}) 9... d5 10. g5 Ne8 11. f4) 9. f4 Rb8 {[%cal
Rb7b4] probably the strongest plan for Black.} (9... b6 10. a4 {[%cal Rc8a6,
Gc3b5] grabbing some space on the queenside and ensuring that Ba6 can be
typically met with Nb5.} Bb7 11. g4 d4 12. Nb5 a6 13. Na3 b5 14. g5 Nd7 15. e5
$5 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gd1h5,Gf1f3,Gf3h3]}) (9... dxe4 10. dxe4 e5 11. Nc4 $1 Qd4+ 12.
Ne3) (9... d4 10. Ne2 Qc7 11. a4 e5 12. Nc4) 10. a4 a6 11. g4 d4 12. Ncb1 e5
13. f5 h6 14. Na3 b5 15. h3 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gd1e1,Ge1g3,Gh3h4,Gg4g5] the engines
naturally prefer Black here but it can be tough for him to come up with a
precise game plan. White's only concern is how to make g4-g5 happen.}) 8... h6
9. Nh3 d5 $1 10. f4 (10. exd5 exd5 11. Nf4 Bg4 12. Qd2 d4 {doesn't look too
great for White}) 10... dxe4 {if Black removes the tension from the center,
White has a choice to go to a quiet positional game with queens off the board,
or still look for complications.} (10... d4 11. Nb1 e5 12. Na3 {with a rich
game for White - he can either close the kingside with f4-f5 and aim for g4-g5,
or keep the pressure on the e5 pawn for a long time, and, at the right moment,
threaten to take on e5 as well.}) (10... Rb8 11. g4 d4 (11... dxe4 12. g5 $1
$13) 12. Nb1 e5 13. f5 Nh7 14. Nd2 {here both of the white knights can join
the attack on the kingside.} b5 (14... Ng5 $6 15. Nxg5 Bxg5 16. Nf3 Bxc1 17.
Rxc1 f6 18. h4 {[%cal Gg4g5]}) 15. a4 a6 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nf3 c4 18. Qe2 {
[%cal Gg1h1,Gf1g1]}) 11. dxe4 (11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gh3f2,Gc1e3]
objectively there's nothing for White if Black plays solid chess but chances
for an attack on the kingside are still there.} Qc7 13. c3 b6 14. Nf2 Bb7 15.
Qh5 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gf2g4]} f5 16. Bg2 Bf6 (16... e5 17. Re1 (17. g4 $5) 17... Bd6
18. Nh3) 17. Re1 Rae8 18. Bd2 Na5 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Re2 Qf7 21. Qf3 $11 {
[%cal Ga1e1]}) 11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Nb4 13. Rd2 Rd8 14. e5 Rxd2 (14... Ng4 15.
Re2) 15. Bxd2 Nfd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. c3 Nc6 18. Nf2 Be6 $11) (5... e5 {Albeit
it is logical for Black to prevent White from playing d2-d4, here I consider
it not a good move for Black. The particular setup for Black is just fine if
White had played 5.Qe2 instead of Nc3 - then the queen doesn't really have
much to do on e2, and White has supposedly "wasted" a tempo by not playing Nc3.
However, now White gets a perfect strategical position with a simple game plan.
} 6. d3 $1 {I think it's important to play d2-d3 before castling as a need for
an earlier maneuver Nf3-d2-c4 might arise, especially if Black is not really
in a hurry with his own castling and intends to start an early kingside
assault with either h7-h5 or h7-h6 and g7-g5.} d6 (6... g6 $6 {Black is too
slow to fianchetto the bishop in this line.} 7. Nd2 Bg7 8. Nc4 {[%csl Rd6]
[%cal Gc3b5]} O-O 9. Nd6 $14 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gd6c8,Gc3d5]}) 7. O-O Be7 8. Nd2 {
[%cal Gd2c4,Gf2f4] White's plan is very straightforward!} (8. h3 O-O 9. Nh4 Nd4
10. Ne2 Ne8 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Nf5 Bg5 13. f4 Bxf5 14. exf5 exf4 15. Bxf4 Bxf4
16. Rxf4 Qb6 17. a4 Nf6 18. a5 Qc5 19. Bxb7 Rab8 20. a6 Rfe8 21. Ra4 Re3 22.
Rf3 Rbe8 23. Rxe3 dxe3 24. Qe2 Qxf5 25. Kg2 h5 26. Rf4 Qe6 27. c4 g5 28. Rf1
Qe5 29. b4 h4 30. gxh4 gxh4 31. Qf3 Qg5+ 32. Kh1 e2 33. Re1 Re3 34. Qg2 Rg3 35.
Qh2 Nh5 36. b5 Nf4 {0-1 (36) Anand,V (2793)-Giri,A (2768) London 2014}) 8...
O-O 9. Nc4 Bg4 {with an idea to provoke f2-f3 so that the bishop can retreat
to e6 and help d6-d5 to happen. On h5 the black bishop has absolutely nothing
to do and can even become a target in a later kingside attack.} (9... Be6 $6 {
would be a serious inaccuracy as White can now simply play} 10. Ne3 {[%cal
Gf2f5,Gg3g5] and it's not clear how Black should stop the f-pawns advancement
and he can't play d6-d5.}) 10. f3 Be6 11. f4 $1 exf4 12. gxf4 d5 13. Ne5 $1 {
I failed to find equality for Black after this move - it's not clear what
exactly he should do now.} Nd4 {perhaps the best defence for Black but it's
not obvious} (13... d4 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Ne2 $14 {[%cal Gb2b3,Ge2g3]}) (13...
g6 14. Nxc6 (14. Kh1 $5 {with the same ideas as in the previous variation})
14... bxc6 15. f5 {[%cal Ge4e5]} gxf5 16. exf5 Bc8 17. Bh6 Re8 18. Kh1 Kh8 19.
