1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 Nc6 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. Qe2 {This is the alternative to the
main move 5.Nc3 which I am proposing to play in Chapter 8 - together they
should form a formidable repertoire to play in many games. Be warned that if
Black plays the best continuations or the main line, the position remains
balanced. You can treat it as some sort of Italian / Ruy Lopez where the ideas
are perhaps more important than exact lines.} e5 {although Black is
voluntarily moving his e-pawn twice in the first five moves, currently, this is
considered to be the best continuation. Black should be flexible on where to
put his d-pawn, either d6 or perhaps even d5. A smart player will delay this
decision thus limiting White's chances.} (5... Be7 6. O-O O-O {[%csl Rc8,Gg2]
in my opinion, this is already a slight inaccuracy - now White gets to execute
the standard idea which guarantees a non-symmetrical pawn structure and a
typical "good bishop" vs "bad bishop". It was not too late for Black to fix
the pawn structure in the centre with either e6-e5, d7-d5 or d7-d6.} 7. e5 Nd5
