best interest to refrain from making an early decision where to put the d-pawn.
Black might even play d7-d5 at some point.} 9. d3 h6 (9... Bf8 {a minor
inaccuracy - Black shouldn't allow White to play Bg5 so easily.} 10. Bg5 d6 11.
Nc4 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Ne3 Qd8 14. Nd2 $14 Be6 15. f4 exf4 16. gxf4 f5 $6 17.
Qf2 $16 Qd7 18. Qg3 Ne7 19. Nf3 fxe4 20. dxe4 Bf7 21. Rad1 Qe6 22. f5 Qxe4 23.
Ng4 Nxf5 24. Nf6+ Kh8 25. Nxe4 Nxg3 26. Nxg3 {1-0 (110) Demchenko,A (2670)
-Quesada Perez, Y (2534) Barcelona 2018}) (9... d6 10. Bg5 (10. Nc4 h6 11. Ne3
Bf8 12. Nd5 {[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1c2] also is interesting.}) 10... h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6
12. Nd2 {[%cal Ga3c4,Gc4e3,Ge3d5,Gf2f4]}) 10. Nc4 Bf8 {the critical moment -
White would love to rearrange his knights to e3 and d2 so that they firmly
control the centre and then either jump to d5 and play on the queenside or
plan a potential f2-f4. The problem is White has to watch out for the d7-d5
thrust which is pretty much inevitable if Black really wants it. So the best
strategy here probably is to "sell" if for the maximum price (have pieces
placed optimally when the breakthrough comes) and be ready to play a good
version of the King's Indian with reversed colours. If you're not ready for it,
perhaps the Chapter 8 continuation is more suitable for you.} 11. a4 {[%csl
Gc4] a useful improving move and also laying a cunning trap.} (11. Ne3 $5 {
another idea, worth to consider.} d5 $1 {clearly the best move} (11... d6 {
after this move I do believe that White can fight for an advantage.} 12. Nd5 $5
$146 Nxd5 (12... Be6 13. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1c2] the knight has the same route - not
necessarily followed by f2-f4, but perhaps b2-b4.} Bxd5 14. exd5 Ne7 15. Nc2 $1
{[%cal Gc2e3,Ga1b1,Gb2b4]} Nfxd5 (15... Qd7 16. Ne3 g6 17. a4 Bg7 18. Bd2 h5
19. Rfb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 16. c4 Nf6 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bg2 {with a small
edge for White.}) 13. exd5 Ne7 14. Ne1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge1c2,Gc2e3,Ge3c4,
Ga2a4,Gf2f4] a new idea - White will base his game on the queenside.} b5 $1 {
probably Black needs to expand on the queenside first and counter White's
ideas before dealing with the kingside.} (14... g6 15. Nc2 Bg7 16. a4 Bd7 17.
Ne3 h5 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 15. Nc2 Bb7 16. Ne3 f5 17. c4
bxc4 18. dxc4 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3,Gf2f4] with a complex and unclear game.}) 12.
exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Nd2 Qd8 15. Nc4 Bf5 (15... Qc7 16. Be3 {[%cal
Ga2a5]}) 16. Be4 Qd7 17. Re1 Rad8 18. a4 Bh3 19. Qf3 Bg4 20. Qg2 Bh3 $11) (11.
Nfd2 $5 {[%cal Gc4e3]} d5 (11... d6 12. Ne3 Be6 13. f4 exf4 14. gxf4 $13) 12.
exd5 Nxd5 13. Re1 Be6 14. Nf3 f6 15. Nh4 Qd7 16. Ng6 Bf7 17. Be4 f5 18. Nxf8
Rxf8 19. Bg2 Rfe8 20. Be3 {also might be playable.}) 11... d6 {Black is
careful. If White will rearrange his knights immediately to e3 and / or d2,
Black can waste a tempo and continue with d6-d5.} (11... d5 $6 {a not so
obvious mistake!} 12. exd5 Qxd5 $146 (12... Nxd5 $2 13. Nfxe5 $1 Nxe5 14. Nxe5
f6 15. Nf7 $3 {[%cal Ge2h5,Gh5d5,Gh5f7] the point! It's very easy to miss this
shot from afar, even for a GM!} Nxc3 (15... Qd7 $2 16. Nxh6+ $1 gxh6 17. Bxd5+
Qxd5 18. Qxe8 Bh3 19. Qe4 Qxe4 20. dxe4 Bxf1 21. Kxf1 $18 {1-0 (37) Longson,A 
(2323)-Lentzos,I (2038) Llandudno 2017}) 16. bxc3 Kxf7 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. Bf4 $16
) 13. a5 {[%cal Ga5a6] the threat of a5-a6 is unstoppable} Bf5 14. Nfxe5 $1 {
is not for this move, Black would be even better.} Qe6 (14... Rxe5 $2 15. Nxe5
Qxe5 16. Qxe5 Nxe5 17. a6 $1 {[%cal Gg2a8]} Nxd3 18. axb7 Rb8 19. Rxa7 $16) 15.
a6 $1 b5 16. Re1 $1 {[%cal Gg2c6]} (16. Bxc6 $2 Qxc6 17. Nxc6 Rxe2 $15) 16...
Nd5 (16... bxc4 17. Bxc6 cxd3 18. Qd1 $14) 17. Ne3 $1 Nxe5 (17... Nxe3 $2 18.
Bxc6 $1 $18) 18. Bxd5 Bxd3 19. Bxe6 Bxe2 20. Bxf7+ Kxf7 21. Rxe2 $14) 12. Re1 {
getting ready for a later d6-d5.} Be6 13. Nfd2 d5 {it will take some
understanding for Black that he can twice move with the e-pawn and then the
d-pawn in such a short period of time, and that it's OK for Black.} (13... g6
14. Ne3 Bg7 (14... d5 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Ne4 {[%cal Ge3d5,Ge4f6]} Kh8 17. Nc4 f5
18. Ned2 Bf7 19. a5 {leads to a complex game.}) 15. Ndc4 {[%cal Ge3d5]} d5 (
15... Qd7 16. Nd5 $1 {and we're back to the idea I already offered before.}
Bxd5 17. exd5 Ne7 18. Ne3 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge1b1,Gb2b4]}) 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. h4
h5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Be4 {[%cal Gc1g5,Ge2f3]}) 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nf3 f6 16. Nh4
$13 {[%cal Gh4g6,Gg2e4,Ga4a6] The game is very complex - we're naturally
playing the King's Indian with reversed colors and a very good version of it.
There is no advantage for White but chances for success definitely are there
- I'd say that the better player will win.} *

