{You've just played a novelty which involves a pawn sacrifice and Black has
accepted the challenge. How can you develop a very dangerous attack?} 9. c4 $3
{the logic dictates to open the position, even if it costs another pawn! The
queen check/pin on a4 will be very unpleasant for Black.} bxc4 (9... Nf6 10.
Nc3 $1 {as long as White ignores the pawn on c4 and concentrates on the attack,
Black will be helpless.} bxc4 11. Bg5 Nbd7 12. Qa4 $18 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5]})
10. Nc3 Nd7 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qa4 e6 13. Bxe4 Qb6 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 15. Qxc4 Qb4 {
[%cal Rb4c4,Rb4e1] [#] Black seemingly has survived the first wave of attacks
and intends to simplify the position. What will you do?} 16. Rxe6+ $3 {There
goes a full rook!} fxe6 17. Qxe6+ Qe7 ({or} 17... Be7 18. Nf5 $40) 18. Qc6 Rb8
19. Bf4 Rb6 20. Qc8+ Qd8 21. Qc4 $40 {despite the fact that White has only two
pawns for the sacrificed rook, his attack is extremely dangerous. Most likely
White will regain the sacrificed material with interest.} *

