{How should White react when Black's knight is on d5?} 6. d4 $1 {If the Black
knight doesn't leave the d5 square voluntarily and Black is willing to
fianchetto the dark-squared bishop on g7 and then attack the centre with d7-d6,
you should get rid of the knight by means of the immediate d2-d4 while it's
not too late and, at the right time, exchange the knights on c6.} (6. O-O $6
Bg7 7. Re1 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. d4 {isn't really great for White as
the black knight still stands on d5 as a nice blockade and you have no access
to the important Bf4 move.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 {[%cal Gg2d5] and there are two
scenarios: if the knight retreats to c7, you can exchange the knights
immediately. If the knight goes to b6, you first defend the pawn on e5, and
only then go for the exchange.} Nc7 (7... Nb6 8. Bf4 (8. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 $1) 8...
Bg7 9. Nxc6 dxc6 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nc3 {[%cal Ge1c1] White is slightly better.
}) 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Re1 O-O 11. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb1c3] with an easy
game for White.} *

