{Your opponent has just played 6...Qe7+ with the idea to force you to trade
queens, and after 7.Be3 meet it with Ng4. What will you do?} 7. Be3 $1 {
You can play it anyway!} Ng4 8. O-O {an easy pawn sacrifice - the logic
dictates that for Black it's very dangerous to accept the pawn sacrifice.} Nxe3
9. fxe3 Nc6 {[#] Black is struggling with his development and something should
be done about it. What should you do here?} (9... Qxe3+ 10. Kh1 {with such an
exposed king and no development this can't end well for Black.} Be6 11. c4 $1 {
[%cal Gb1c3,Gf1e1,Gd4d5]}) 10. c4 $1 {of course, open the position!} dxc4 11.
d5 $1 Ne5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 {[#] Black feels alright, he just needs to play Bd6
and short castle...} 13. Na3 $1 {a very strong move which underlines that the
whole concept of playing the Qe7+ was just wrong.} Bd6 14. Nxc4 Qe7 15. e4 $1 {
[%cal Ge4e5,Gd5d6] because of the e4-e5 and d5-d6 threats Black is obliged to
waste one more tempo for the blockade.} Be5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Qc2 {[%csl Rc5]
and suddenly Black has no time to protect the pawn on c5, and the king is
still in the centre!} b6 18. b4 $1 {[%cal Gc2c6]} Qd4+ 19. Kh1 Qxb4 20. e5 O-O
21. e6 {White is easily winning - Black's extra pawn is irrelevant.} Ba6 22.
Rxf7 Rxf7 23. exf7+ Kxf7 24. Qf5+ Kg8 25. d6 Rd8 26. Bd5+ Kh8 27. Be4 $18 *

